{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_016WvPkqL21dQeFhxDuCgoE5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01XEjumaJqcF7bMfBZFh8zrA","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport pypdf\nreader = pypdf.PdfReader('/tmp/quadrant_paper/paper.pdf')\nprint(f'Pages: {len(reader.pages)}')\ntext = ''\nfor p in reader.pages:\n    text += p.extract_text() + '\\n\\n'\nwith open('/tmp/quadrant_paper/paper.txt', 'w') as f:\n    f.write(text)\nprint(f'Wrote {len(text)} chars')\n\"\nwc -l /tmp/quadrant_paper/paper.txt\nhead -80 /tmp/quadrant_paper/paper.txt","description":"Extract PDF text via pypdf"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":543,"cache_read_input_tokens":80527,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":543},"output_tokens":68,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"13daff1f-340d-492f-844d-6b56324305f0"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XEjumaJqcF7bMfBZFh8zrA","type":"tool_result","content":"Pages: 15\nWrote 55895 chars\n1864 /tmp/quadrant_paper/paper.txt\n000\n001\n002\n003\n004\n005\n006\n007\n008\n009\n010\n011\n012\n013\n014\n015\n016\n017\n018\n019\n020\n021\n022\n023\n024\n025\n026\n027\n028\n029\n030\n031\n032\n033\n034\n035\n036\n037\n038\n039\n040\n041\n042\n043\n044\n045\n046\n047\n048\n049\n050\n051\n052\n053\n054\nWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\nAnonymous Authors1\nAbstract\nPrior work has shown that safety interventions\napplied during pretraining, such as removing and\nrephrasing harmful content, can substantially im-\nprove the robustness of the resulting models. In\nthis paper, we study the fundamental question\nthat prior work has overlooked:“When during\npretraining should safety interventions be intro-\nduced?”We keep the underlying data sources\nand pretraining interventions fixed, varying the\nintervention start time (after 0%, 20%, or 60%\nof pretraining tokens). We find that the optimal\nstart time is not one-size-fits-all: with standard\ntop-kdecoding, introducing interventions after a\nshort initial phase of safe-only pretraining (20%-\n60%) often yields the strongest robustness, with\nthe clearest benefits emergingafterdownstream,\nbenign finetuning. In contrast, for safety-aware in-\nference, interventions starting from the beginning\nimprove steerability towards safer generations.\nFinally, we observe that earlier interventions re-\nshape internal representations: linear probes more\ncleanly separate safe vs harmful examples. Our","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"829f441c-b308-4d98-b092-615965dea292","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:19:58.548Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"Pages: 15\nWrote 55895 chars\n1864 /tmp/quadrant_paper/paper.txt\n000\n001\n002\n003\n004\n005\n006\n007\n008\n009\n010\n011\n012\n013\n014\n015\n016\n017\n018\n019\n020\n021\n022\n023\n024\n025\n026\n027\n028\n029\n030\n031\n032\n033\n034\n035\n036\n037\n038\n039\n040\n041\n042\n043\n044\n045\n046\n047\n048\n049\n050\n051\n052\n053\n054\nWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\nAnonymous Authors1\nAbstract\nPrior work has shown that safety interventions\napplied during pretraining, such as removing and\nrephrasing harmful content, can substantially im-\nprove the robustness of the resulting models. In\nthis paper, we study the fundamental question\nthat prior work has overlooked:“When during\npretraining should safety interventions be intro-\nduced?”We keep the underlying data sources\nand pretraining interventions fixed, varying the\nintervention start time (after 0%, 20%, or 60%\nof pretraining tokens). We find that the optimal\nstart time is not one-size-fits-all: with standard\ntop-kdecoding, introducing interventions after a\nshort initial phase of safe-only pretraining (20%-\n60%) often yields the strongest robustness, with\nthe clearest benefits emergingafterdownstream,\nbenign finetuning. In contrast, for safety-aware in-\nference, interventions starting from the beginning\nimprove steerability towards safer generations.\nFinally, we observe that earlier interventions re-\nshape internal representations: linear probes more\ncleanly separate safe vs harmful examples. Our","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
