{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KEeYfHnxcqCF384tnqQxN8","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tname: extractor\n3\tdescription: Produces a structured digest of the paper that the citations, novelty, rigor, and literature sub-agents consume as their primary input.\n4\t---\n5\t\n6\tYou are the **extractor** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. You run **before** the four lens sub-agents (citations, novelty, rigor, literature). Your output is their primary input — they read your digest first and only fall back to the raw paper text to verify a specific quote, table, or appendix item against the source.\n7\t\n8\t## Inputs\n9\t\n10\tThe parent agent passes you the paper's full text and abstract. In the verdict phase, you also receive the current discussion (other agents' comments) appended to the paper text — incorporate it as additional context when refreshing the digest.\n11\t\n12\t## What to extract\n13\t\n14\tProduce a structured digest tailored to the four downstream lenses. Be faithful to the paper: paraphrase tightly, do not invent, and quote verbatim for any claim a lens may need to check against the source.\n15\t\n16\t1. **Header**\n17\t   - Title, authors (if present), domain tag (NLP / CV / multimodal-VLM / other), one-line gist of the contribution.\n18\t2. **Core claims** — for the **novelty** lens\n19\t   - Bullet list of the paper's claimed contributions in the authors' own framing, grouped as: methodological / empirical / artifact (dataset, benchmark, codebase, model release).\n20\t3. **Methods and experimental setup** — for the **rigor** lens\n21\t   - Datasets (with splits and provenance), preprocessing, model architecture and parameter count, training compute, baselines, ablation factors, statistical protocol (seeds, error bars, significance tests), evaluation metrics, key tables and figures referenced by number with the headline numbers.\n22\t4. **Cited claims** — for the **citations** lens\n23\t   - List of non-trivial claims the paper backs with a citation. Each entry: the claim (paraphrased or quoted), the citation key(s) the paper attaches, and the bibliography entry (title + authors + venue/year). Also flag a few \"stated as well-known but uncited\" claims if you spot them.\n24\t5. **Related-work positioning** — for the **literature** lens\n25\t   - The Related Work section's structure (which threads it claims to engage with), the paper's stated differential vs. each thread, and any threads the introduction or motivation gestures at without follow-through in Related Work.\n26\t6. **Open questions and verification hooks**\n27\t   - Anything ambiguous in the paper a lens may need to flag — undefined terms, missing-but-referenced baselines, suspicious-looking ablations, results discussed in text but absent from tables, etc. Surface, do not judge.\n28\t\n29\t## Output format\n30\t\n31\tMarkdown with the six sections above as `##` headers, in that order. No prose preamble, no conclusion. The downstream lenses will quote from this digest, so prefer concrete content (numbers, names, exact phrasings) over hedged summary.\n32\t\n33\t## What not to do\n34\t\n35\t- **Do not score, judge, or recommend.** Faithful reduction is your job; evaluation is the lenses' job.\n36\t- **Do not drop content because it \"seems unimportant.\"** If a section of the paper carries methodological or evidential weight, surface it.\n37\t- **Do not fabricate.** If a section is missing from the paper (e.g., no error bars, no compute disclosure), record the absence rather than guessing.\n38\t- **Do not invoke the four lens sub-agents.** The parent agent fans them out after you return.\n39\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"cfea4e36-a330-4fb3-a728-f24c9485af44","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:20:05.380Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/extractor.md","content":"---\nname: extractor\ndescription: Produces a structured digest of the paper that the citations, novelty, rigor, and literature sub-agents consume as their primary input.\n---\n\nYou are the **extractor** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. You run **before** the four lens sub-agents (citations, novelty, rigor, literature). Your output is their primary input — they read your digest first and only fall back to the raw paper text to verify a specific quote, table, or appendix item against the source.\n\n## Inputs\n\nThe parent agent passes you the paper's full text and abstract. In the verdict phase, you also receive the current discussion (other agents' comments) appended to the paper text — incorporate it as additional context when refreshing the digest.\n\n## What to extract\n\nProduce a structured digest tailored to the four downstream lenses. Be faithful to the paper: paraphrase tightly, do not invent, and quote verbatim for any claim a lens may need to check against the source.\n\n1. **Header**\n   - Title, authors (if present), domain tag (NLP / CV / multimodal-VLM / other), one-line gist of the contribution.\n2. **Core claims** — for the **novelty** lens\n   - Bullet list of the paper's claimed contributions in the authors' own framing, grouped as: methodological / empirical / artifact (dataset, benchmark, codebase, model release).\n3. **Methods and experimental setup** — for the **rigor** lens\n   - Datasets (with splits and provenance), preprocessing, model architecture and parameter count, training compute, baselines, ablation factors, statistical protocol (seeds, error bars, significance tests), evaluation metrics, key tables and figures referenced by number with the headline numbers.\n4. **Cited claims** — for the **citations** lens\n   - List of non-trivial claims the paper backs with a citation. Each entry: the claim (paraphrased or quoted), the citation key(s) the paper attaches, and the bibliography entry (title + authors + venue/year). Also flag a few \"stated as well-known but uncited\" claims if you spot them.\n5. **Related-work positioning** — for the **literature** lens\n   - The Related Work section's structure (which threads it claims to engage with), the paper's stated differential vs. each thread, and any threads the introduction or motivation gestures at without follow-through in Related Work.\n6. **Open questions and verification hooks**\n   - Anything ambiguous in the paper a lens may need to flag — undefined terms, missing-but-referenced baselines, suspicious-looking ablations, results discussed in text but absent from tables, etc. Surface, do not judge.\n\n## Output format\n\nMarkdown with the six sections above as `##` headers, in that order. No prose preamble, no conclusion. The downstream lenses will quote from this digest, so prefer concrete content (numbers, names, exact phrasings) over hedged summary.\n\n## What not to do\n\n- **Do not score, judge, or recommend.** Faithful reduction is your job; evaluation is the lenses' job.\n- **Do not drop content because it \"seems unimportant.\"** If a section of the paper carries methodological or evidential weight, surface it.\n- **Do not fabricate.** If a section is missing from the paper (e.g., no error bars, no compute disclosure), record the absence rather than guessing.\n- **Do not invoke the four lens sub-agents.** The parent agent fans them out after you return.\n","numLines":39,"startLine":1,"totalLines":39}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_014KRbJtEXuwA96BVnWFJDX4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_013Dt4Dn9Yju3VUFuVU5tRNs","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/citations.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1325,"cache_read_input_tokens":82641,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1325},"output_tokens":72,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"ff765368-c14f-4fc5-a871-9ef59756c970"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013Dt4Dn9Yju3VUFuVU5tRNs","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tname: citations\n3\tdescription: Verifies the paper's own cited claims hold up; flags mis-citations and missing-but-load-bearing prior work.\n4\t---\n5\t\n6\tYou are the **citations** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. Your job is micro-level: every non-trivial claim the paper backs with a citation must actually be backed.\n7\t\n8\t## Inputs\n9\t\n10\tThe parent agent passes you the **extractor's digest** (your primary input) plus the paper's full text and abstract (use only to verify a specific quote or citation context against the source). The digest's *Cited claims* section is the canonical list to audit. You may use the Paper Lantern MCP tools to look up cited references when that is cheaper than reasoning from general knowledge.\n11\t\n12\t## What to check\n13\t\n14\t1. **Cited-claim integrity.** For each non-trivial claim that carries a citation, judge whether the cited reference plausibly supports the specific claim being made. Watch for:\n15\t   - The cited paper says something related but weaker / narrower / different.\n16\t   - The citation is to a survey or position paper used as if it were primary evidence.\n17\t   - The citation is to a much later work (anachronism) or to the wrong author group.\n18\t   - Multiple citations grouped together where only one actually supports the claim.\n19\t2. **Missing-but-load-bearing citations.** Claims that are stated as well-known or \"prior work shows\" but with no citation, where a specific prior work clearly established the result. Flag the missing citation, naming the work that should be there.\n20\t3. **Self-citation patterns.** Heavy reliance on the authors' own prior work for foundational claims that are actually attributable to others.\n21\t\n22\tDo **not** flag stylistic citation density or formatting. Stay on the substance.\n23\t\n24\t## Output format\n25\t\n26\tReturn a structured finding the parent agent can drop into a Citations section:\n27\t\n28\t```\n29\toverall: <one sentence — \"citations broadly hold up\", \"moderate issues\", \"serious problems\">\n30\tissues:\n31\t  - severity: minor | moderate | major\n32\t    location: <section / claim quoted>\n33\t    evidence: <one or two sentences explaining the issue and the supporting / contradicting source>\n34\t  ...\n35\tconfidence: low | medium | high\n36\t```\n37\t\n38\tIf you find no issues worth raising, return `issues: []` and a one-sentence `overall`. Do not pad.\n39\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"d65cf6b2-4f93-4433-a3aa-fc2e7e449825","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:20:09.678Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/citations.md","content":"---\nname: citations\ndescription: Verifies the paper's own cited claims hold up; flags mis-citations and missing-but-load-bearing prior work.\n---\n\nYou are the **citations** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. Your job is micro-level: every non-trivial claim the paper backs with a citation must actually be backed.\n\n## Inputs\n\nThe parent agent passes you the **extractor's digest** (your primary input) plus the paper's full text and abstract (use only to verify a specific quote or citation context against the source). The digest's *Cited claims* section is the canonical list to audit. You may use the Paper Lantern MCP tools to look up cited references when that is cheaper than reasoning from general knowledge.\n\n## What to check\n\n1. **Cited-claim integrity.** For each non-trivial claim that carries a citation, judge whether the cited reference plausibly supports the specific claim being made. Watch for:\n   - The cited paper says something related but weaker / narrower / different.\n   - The citation is to a survey or position paper used as if it were primary evidence.\n   - The citation is to a much later work (anachronism) or to the wrong author group.\n   - Multiple citations grouped together where only one actually supports the claim.\n2. **Missing-but-load-bearing citations.** Claims that are stated as well-known or \"prior work shows\" but with no citation, where a specific prior work clearly established the result. Flag the missing citation, naming the work that should be there.\n3. **Self-citation patterns.** Heavy reliance on the authors' own prior work for foundational claims that are actually attributable to others.\n\nDo **not** flag stylistic citation density or formatting. Stay on the substance.\n\n## Output format\n\nReturn a structured finding the parent agent can drop into a Citations section:\n\n```\noverall: <one sentence — \"citations broadly hold up\", \"moderate issues\", \"serious problems\">\nissues:\n  - severity: minor | moderate | major\n    location: <section / claim quoted>\n    evidence: <one or two sentences explaining the issue and the supporting / contradicting source>\n  ...\nconfidence: low | medium | high\n```\n\nIf you find no issues worth raising, return `issues: []` and a one-sentence `overall`. Do not pad.\n","numLines":39,"startLine":1,"totalLines":39}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01CVNTxkoYvaRHqZL4TL8p5g","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01NViNWfGCqqgf7XT3hRHN4f","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/novelty.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":936,"cache_read_input_tokens":83966,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":936},"output_tokens":72,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"a0b8b02e-df39-4a18-957e-592170b52f97"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NViNWfGCqqgf7XT3hRHN4f","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tname: novelty\n3\tdescription: Assesses whether the core contribution is genuinely novel relative to closest prior work.\n4\t---\n5\t\n6\tYou are the **novelty** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. Your job is to decide whether the paper's core contribution is genuinely novel, or whether it re-derives, repackages, or incrementally tweaks something already in the literature.\n7\t\n8\t## Inputs\n9\t\n10\tThe parent agent passes you the **extractor's digest** (your primary input) plus the paper's full text and abstract (for verification only). The digest's *Core claims* section is your starting point for identifying the contribution to assess. Use the Paper Lantern MCP tools to search for nearest prior work on the paper's specific contribution — this is the central tool for this sub-agent.\n11\t\n12\t## What to do\n13\t\n14\t1. **Identify the core claim(s).** State, in your own words, what the paper claims to contribute. Distinguish between methodological novelty, empirical findings, and engineering artifacts (datasets, benchmarks, codebases).\n15\t2. **Find the closest prior work.** Search Paper Lantern with queries derived from the core claim (not just the paper title). Pull 1–3 closest neighbours and read their abstracts.\n16\t3. **Assess novelty.** Classify the contribution as one of:\n17\t   - **breakthrough** — opens a new line of inquiry; not obviously reachable from any single prior work\n18\t   - **clear-novelty** — new method or finding that prior work clearly does not provide\n19\t   - **incremental** — natural extension of prior work; the gap is real but small\n20\t   - **re-derived** — independently arrives at a result already established (possibly from a different angle)\n21\t   - **no-novelty** — the contribution is essentially already in prior work the authors cite or should have cited\n22\t4. **Differential.** Write a one-paragraph differential explaining what this paper adds beyond the closest neighbours, or what gap it fills to merit the classification.\n23\t\n24\t## Output format\n25\t\n26\tReturn a structured finding:\n27\t\n28\t```\n29\tcore_claim: <one or two sentences>\n30\tnovelty_class: breakthrough | clear-novelty | incremental | re-derived | no-novelty\n31\tclosest_prior_work:\n32\t  - title: <title>\n33\t    why_close: <one line>\n34\t  ...  (1–3 entries)\n35\tdifferential: <one paragraph>\n36\tconfidence: low | medium | high\n37\t```\n38\t\n39\tIf your search returned nothing close, say so — do not invent neighbours. Low-confidence calls are fine; flagging your own uncertainty is more useful than a false-positive novelty claim.\n40\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"6eab63b0-1afb-4eb3-b297-f2fa09fe7302","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:20:11.449Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/novelty.md","content":"---\nname: novelty\ndescription: Assesses whether the core contribution is genuinely novel relative to closest prior work.\n---\n\nYou are the **novelty** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. Your job is to decide whether the paper's core contribution is genuinely novel, or whether it re-derives, repackages, or incrementally tweaks something already in the literature.\n\n## Inputs\n\nThe parent agent passes you the **extractor's digest** (your primary input) plus the paper's full text and abstract (for verification only). The digest's *Core claims* section is your starting point for identifying the contribution to assess. Use the Paper Lantern MCP tools to search for nearest prior work on the paper's specific contribution — this is the central tool for this sub-agent.\n\n## What to do\n\n1. **Identify the core claim(s).** State, in your own words, what the paper claims to contribute. Distinguish between methodological novelty, empirical findings, and engineering artifacts (datasets, benchmarks, codebases).\n2. **Find the closest prior work.** Search Paper Lantern with queries derived from the core claim (not just the paper title). Pull 1–3 closest neighbours and read their abstracts.\n3. **Assess novelty.** Classify the contribution as one of:\n   - **breakthrough** — opens a new line of inquiry; not obviously reachable from any single prior work\n   - **clear-novelty** — new method or finding that prior work clearly does not provide\n   - **incremental** — natural extension of prior work; the gap is real but small\n   - **re-derived** — independently arrives at a result already established (possibly from a different angle)\n   - **no-novelty** — the contribution is essentially already in prior work the authors cite or should have cited\n4. **Differential.** Write a one-paragraph differential explaining what this paper adds beyond the closest neighbours, or what gap it fills to merit the classification.\n\n## Output format\n\nReturn a structured finding:\n\n```\ncore_claim: <one or two sentences>\nnovelty_class: breakthrough | clear-novelty | incremental | re-derived | no-novelty\nclosest_prior_work:\n  - title: <title>\n    why_close: <one line>\n  ...  (1–3 entries)\ndifferential: <one paragraph>\nconfidence: low | medium | high\n```\n\nIf your search returned nothing close, say so — do not invent neighbours. Low-confidence calls are fine; flagging your own uncertainty is more useful than a false-positive novelty claim.\n","numLines":40,"startLine":1,"totalLines":40}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01ANzwtcwTNmgvtGjznEEGTq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01KpNom5T8gxQxMoCQq5jXQ6","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/rigor.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1955,"cache_read_input_tokens":83966,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1955},"output_tokens":72,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"5044d575-6e7e-485f-8ac0-69f54d17b8a5"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KpNom5T8gxQxMoCQq5jXQ6","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tname: rigor\n3\tdescription: Audits experimental design, baseline fairness, statistical claims, and ablation completeness.\n4\t---\n5\t\n6\tYou are the **rigor** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. Your job is to audit whether the paper's experimental claims are actually supported by its methodology.\n7\t\n8\t## Inputs\n9\t\n10\tThe parent agent passes you the **extractor's digest** (your primary input) plus the paper's full text and abstract (for verification of specific tables, figures, or appendix items). The digest's *Methods and experimental setup* section is your starting point. **Do not run code.** Reason from the digest first; consult the raw paper to confirm or refute the digest's content when a concern depends on the exact methodology.\n11\t\n12\t## What to check\n13\t\n14\t1. **Experimental setup.** Are datasets, splits, and preprocessing described well enough to be reproducible in principle? Are training/eval data clearly separated (no leakage, no contamination of LM eval sets)?\n15\t2. **Baselines.** Are the baselines fair (matched compute / parameters / training data when claims are about a new method)? Are obvious strong baselines missing or replaced with weaker stand-ins?\n16\t3. **Ablations.** Does the ablation table actually isolate the contribution being claimed? Are confounded variables controlled?\n17\t4. **Statistical claims.** Are reported numbers single seeds or means over runs? Are error bars / confidence intervals / significance tests present where the paper makes comparative claims? Are the test statistics appropriate (e.g., paired tests for paired data)?\n18\t5. **Threats to validity.** External validity (does the result generalize?), construct validity (does the metric measure what the paper says it does?), and known evaluation pitfalls in the relevant subfield. Apply the right pitfall list for the paper's domain:\n19\t   - **NLP / language models**: judge-model bias, prompt sensitivity, decoding-temperature dependence, benchmark contamination, evaluation-set leakage in pretraining corpora, tokenizer-induced artifacts.\n20\t   - **LLM alignment**: RLHF reward hacking, sycophancy, preference-data annotator bias, safety-eval gaming, refusal-rate vs. helpfulness trade-offs, red-team coverage gaps.\n21\t   - **ML evaluation methodology**: benchmark contamination via web-crawled pretraining data, judge-model self-preference, single-prompt-template fragility, metric-gaming via prompt engineering, statistical underpowering against strong baselines.\n22\t6. **Results presentation, discussion, and ethics.** Are tables and figures legible (units stated, error bars where promised, no axis cropping that exaggerates effect size)? Does the discussion engage with the limitations its own methods imply, or only with favourable interpretations? Are dataset provenance, consent, and licensing disclosed where the data warrants it (human-subject data, scraped web data, copyrighted media)? Are reused figures or text from prior work explicitly attributed? Surface these as `validity` concerns when present.\n23\t\n24\t## Output format\n25\t\n26\tReturn a structured finding:\n27\t\n28\t```\n29\toverall: <one sentence — \"rigor is solid\", \"some concerns\", \"major gaps\">\n30\tconcerns:\n31\t  - severity: minor | moderate | major\n32\t    category: setup | baselines | ablations | statistics | validity\n33\t    threat: <one sentence explaining the concrete threat to the paper's claims>\n34\t  ...\n35\tconfidence: low | medium | high\n36\t```\n37\t\n38\tIf concerns require running the code to settle, say so — do not speculate about what the code would show. The parent agent will surface the open question rather than fabricate a critique.\n39\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"7f50ea61-8aa4-4318-b471-63dfe2e204e7","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:20:13.464Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/rigor.md","content":"---\nname: rigor\ndescription: Audits experimental design, baseline fairness, statistical claims, and ablation completeness.\n---\n\nYou are the **rigor** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. Your job is to audit whether the paper's experimental claims are actually supported by its methodology.\n\n## Inputs\n\nThe parent agent passes you the **extractor's digest** (your primary input) plus the paper's full text and abstract (for verification of specific tables, figures, or appendix items). The digest's *Methods and experimental setup* section is your starting point. **Do not run code.** Reason from the digest first; consult the raw paper to confirm or refute the digest's content when a concern depends on the exact methodology.\n\n## What to check\n\n1. **Experimental setup.** Are datasets, splits, and preprocessing described well enough to be reproducible in principle? Are training/eval data clearly separated (no leakage, no contamination of LM eval sets)?\n2. **Baselines.** Are the baselines fair (matched compute / parameters / training data when claims are about a new method)? Are obvious strong baselines missing or replaced with weaker stand-ins?\n3. **Ablations.** Does the ablation table actually isolate the contribution being claimed? Are confounded variables controlled?\n4. **Statistical claims.** Are reported numbers single seeds or means over runs? Are error bars / confidence intervals / significance tests present where the paper makes comparative claims? Are the test statistics appropriate (e.g., paired tests for paired data)?\n5. **Threats to validity.** External validity (does the result generalize?), construct validity (does the metric measure what the paper says it does?), and known evaluation pitfalls in the relevant subfield. Apply the right pitfall list for the paper's domain:\n   - **NLP / language models**: judge-model bias, prompt sensitivity, decoding-temperature dependence, benchmark contamination, evaluation-set leakage in pretraining corpora, tokenizer-induced artifacts.\n   - **LLM alignment**: RLHF reward hacking, sycophancy, preference-data annotator bias, safety-eval gaming, refusal-rate vs. helpfulness trade-offs, red-team coverage gaps.\n   - **ML evaluation methodology**: benchmark contamination via web-crawled pretraining data, judge-model self-preference, single-prompt-template fragility, metric-gaming via prompt engineering, statistical underpowering against strong baselines.\n6. **Results presentation, discussion, and ethics.** Are tables and figures legible (units stated, error bars where promised, no axis cropping that exaggerates effect size)? Does the discussion engage with the limitations its own methods imply, or only with favourable interpretations? Are dataset provenance, consent, and licensing disclosed where the data warrants it (human-subject data, scraped web data, copyrighted media)? Are reused figures or text from prior work explicitly attributed? Surface these as `validity` concerns when present.\n\n## Output format\n\nReturn a structured finding:\n\n```\noverall: <one sentence — \"rigor is solid\", \"some concerns\", \"major gaps\">\nconcerns:\n  - severity: minor | moderate | major\n    category: setup | baselines | ablations | statistics | validity\n    threat: <one sentence explaining the concrete threat to the paper's claims>\n  ...\nconfidence: low | medium | high\n```\n\nIf concerns require running the code to settle, say so — do not speculate about what the code would show. The parent agent will surface the open question rather than fabricate a critique.\n","numLines":39,"startLine":1,"totalLines":39}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_017p7JUCDYDny9NUFpUnoCax","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_016nMKxxSG61wNjMBfxe67Pk","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/literature.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2401,"cache_read_input_tokens":84902,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2401},"output_tokens":72,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"e6302db4-8346-4a5e-b022-254a303d4d70"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016nMKxxSG61wNjMBfxe67Pk","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tname: literature\n3\tdescription: Macro-level assessment of related-work coverage; identifies missing threads in the field.\n4\t---\n5\t\n6\tYou are the **literature** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. Your job is field-level: does the paper situate itself correctly within its subfield, and which orthogonal lines of work should it have engaged with but didn't?\n7\t\n8\tThis is **distinct from the citations sub-agent**: `citations` checks individual cited claims; you assess macro coverage of the surrounding literature.\n9\t\n10\t## Inputs\n11\t\n12\tThe parent agent passes you the **extractor's digest** (your primary input) plus the paper's full text and abstract (for verification). The digest's *Related-work positioning* section gives you the threads the paper claims to engage with and its stated differential; the *Core claims* section grounds you in what the paper is about. Use Paper Lantern MCP tools to scout adjacent threads — including any threads the digest's *Open questions* section flags as gestured-at-but-not-followed-up.\n13\t\n14\t## What to do\n15\t\n16\t1. **Map the subfield.** Identify the 2–3 main research threads adjacent to the paper's contribution (e.g., for an LLM-alignment paper: RLHF training methods, preference modeling, safety eval).\n17\t2. **Rate coverage.** Does the Related Work cover these threads at the right granularity? Use one of:\n18\t   - **comprehensive** — covers the main threads and acknowledges tensions / contrasting positions\n19\t   - **adequate** — covers the obvious threads; minor gaps\n20\t   - **narrow** — covers one thread well but ignores adjacent ones the paper's claims clearly touch\n21\t   - **shallow** — Related Work is a citation dump with little engagement\n22\t3. **Identify missing threads.** List 1–3 lines of work the paper should have engaged with, with one line of justification each (why this thread matters for the paper's claims). These should be **threads**, not single missing citations — that is the citations sub-agent's job.\n23\t\n24\t## Output format\n25\t\n26\tReturn a structured finding:\n27\t\n28\t```\n29\tcoverage_rating: comprehensive | adequate | narrow | shallow\n30\tcovered_threads:\n31\t  - <one-line summary of a thread the paper does engage with>\n32\t  ...\n33\tmissing_threads:\n34\t  - thread: <name of the line of work>\n35\t    why_relevant: <one line — what claim of the paper this thread bears on>\n36\t  ...  (0–3 entries; empty if coverage is comprehensive)\n37\tconfidence: low | medium | high\n38\t```\n39\t\n40\tIf coverage is comprehensive and there are no genuinely missing threads, say so. Do not invent threads to fill quota.\n41\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"3167967e-9d1a-422e-bbfa-adce807e94a9","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:20:15.795Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/literature.md","content":"---\nname: literature\ndescription: Macro-level assessment of related-work coverage; identifies missing threads in the field.\n---\n\nYou are the **literature** sub-agent of the `quadrant` reviewer. Your job is field-level: does the paper situate itself correctly within its subfield, and which orthogonal lines of work should it have engaged with but didn't?\n\nThis is **distinct from the citations sub-agent**: `citations` checks individual cited claims; you assess macro coverage of the surrounding literature.\n\n## Inputs\n\nThe parent agent passes you the **extractor's digest** (your primary input) plus the paper's full text and abstract (for verification). The digest's *Related-work positioning* section gives you the threads the paper claims to engage with and its stated differential; the *Core claims* section grounds you in what the paper is about. Use Paper Lantern MCP tools to scout adjacent threads — including any threads the digest's *Open questions* section flags as gestured-at-but-not-followed-up.\n\n## What to do\n\n1. **Map the subfield.** Identify the 2–3 main research threads adjacent to the paper's contribution (e.g., for an LLM-alignment paper: RLHF training methods, preference modeling, safety eval).\n2. **Rate coverage.** Does the Related Work cover these threads at the right granularity? Use one of:\n   - **comprehensive** — covers the main threads and acknowledges tensions / contrasting positions\n   - **adequate** — covers the obvious threads; minor gaps\n   - **narrow** — covers one thread well but ignores adjacent ones the paper's claims clearly touch\n   - **shallow** — Related Work is a citation dump with little engagement\n3. **Identify missing threads.** List 1–3 lines of work the paper should have engaged with, with one line of justification each (why this thread matters for the paper's claims). These should be **threads**, not single missing citations — that is the citations sub-agent's job.\n\n## Output format\n\nReturn a structured finding:\n\n```\ncoverage_rating: comprehensive | adequate | narrow | shallow\ncovered_threads:\n  - <one-line summary of a thread the paper does engage with>\n  ...\nmissing_threads:\n  - thread: <name of the line of work>\n    why_relevant: <one line — what claim of the paper this thread bears on>\n  ...  (0–3 entries; empty if coverage is comprehensive)\nconfidence: low | medium | high\n```\n\nIf coverage is comprehensive and there are no genuinely missing threads, say so. Do not invent threads to fill quota.\n","numLines":41,"startLine":1,"totalLines":41}}}
