{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BMvbe9v9uJKxyNUWzz84pR","type":"tool_result","content":"1\tWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n2\tAnonymous Authors1\n3\tAbstract\n4\tPrior work has shown that safety interventions\n5\tapplied during pretraining, such as removing and\n6\trephrasing harmful content, can substantially im-\n7\tprove the robustness of the resulting models. In\n8\tthis paper, we study the fundamental question\n9\tthat prior work has overlooked:“When during\n10\tpretraining should safety interventions be intro-\n11\tduced?”We keep the underlying data sources\n12\tand pretraining interventions fixed, varying the\n13\tintervention start time (after 0%, 20%, or 60%\n14\tof pretraining tokens). We find that the optimal\n15\tstart time is not one-size-fits-all: with standard\n16\ttop-kdecoding, introducing interventions after a\n17\tshort initial phase of safe-only pretraining (20%-\n18\t60%) often yields the strongest robustness, with\n19\tthe clearest benefits emergingafterdownstream,\n20\tbenign finetuning. In contrast, for safety-aware in-\n21\tference, interventions starting from the beginning\n22\timprove steerability towards safer generations.\n23\tFinally, we observe that earlier interventions re-\n24\tshape internal representations: linear probes more\n25\tcleanly separate safe vs harmful examples. Our\n26\tresults are the first to establish intervention timing\n27\tas a key curriculum design choice for safety.\n28\t1. Introduction\n29\tLarge language models (LLMs) are increasingly de-\n30\tployed in high-stakes settings, such as medical domains\n31\t(Thirunavukarasu et al., 2023; Li ´evin et al., 2024), social\n32\tsciences and simulations (Ziems et al., 2024; Byun et al.,\n33\t2025), and in robotics (Firoozi et al., 2025; Robey et al.,\n34\t2024), where unsafe generations can cause real-world harms.\n35\tMost production systems still rely on post-hoc alignment\n36\t(e.g., RLHF (Ouyang et al., 2022), DPO (Rafailov et al.,\n37\t2023), or constitutional variants (Bai et al., 2022)) that re-\n38\tshape surface model behavior after completing pretraining.\n39\tYet, a growing body of evidence suggests these methods are\n40\t1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\n41\tAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n42\t<anon.email@domain.com>.\n43\tPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\n44\ton Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\n45\tbrittle: alignment effects are often restricted to the first few\n46\ttokens of a response (Qi et al., 2024b) and are easily circum-\n47\tvented by benign finetuning (Qi et al., 2024a) or adversarial\n48\tpressure through prompting (Zou et al., 2023; Chao et al.,\n49\t2023). Misaligned behavior can be further elicited, and even\n50\tamplified, by malicious or adversarial finetuning on a single\n51\ttask, which has been shown to generalize to other harmful\n52\ttasks (Betley et al., 2025).\n53\tThese vulnerabilities have motivated a shift toward inte-\n54\tgrating safety directly into pretraining. Recent work has\n55\texplored removing all harmful content from pretraining\n56\tdata via filtering approaches (O’Brien et al., 2025). Other\n57\twork, however, has demonstrated that this could lead to\n58\ta lack of understanding of harmful content, making mod-\n59\tels more prone to comply with harmful requests (Li et al.,\n60\t2025). More promisingly, Maini et al. (2025) explored syn-\n61\tthetic pretraining interventions that maintain information\n62\tfrom harmful examples while removing explicitly harm-\n63\tful content or providing sufficient context about why such\n64\tcontent is harmful. These safety pretraining interventions\n65\tshow promise for improving refusal behavior, robustness to\n66\tadversarial jailbreaks, and resilience to benign finetuning.\n67\tDespite this progress, all prior work on safety pretraining\n68\tapplies interventions uniformly from the start of training,\n69\timplicitly assuming thatwhensafety signals are introduced\n70\tdoes not matter. We challenge this assumption. Drawing\n71\ton insights from curriculum learning (Bengio et al., 2009;\n72\tGraves et al., 2017), which has shown that the ordering\n73\tof training examples can qualitatively change downstream\n74\tperformance, we ask:when during pretraining should\n75\tsafety interventions be introduced?This question has\n76\tnatural intuitions on both sides: interventions introduced too\n77\tlate may be superficial and easily removed by downstream\n78\tfinetuning, while interventions introduced too early may\n79\tdegrade capabilities or over-regularize the model before it\n80\thas learned basic linguistic structure. To our knowledge, we\n81\tare the first to systematically study this question.\n82\tIn this paper, we empirically study the impacts of introduc-\n83\ting safety interventions at different times during pretrain-\n84\ting. We adopt the various pretraining interventions from the\n85\twork of Maini et al. (2025), such as synthetic rephrasing and\n86\tcontextualization, metadata annotation, and refusal training,\n87\tand introduce them at different stages (i.e., after 0%, 20%,\n88\tor 60% of the total amount of 600B tokens) of pretrain-\n89\t1\n90\t\n91\tWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n92\t0% 20% 60% 100%\n93\tPretraining Intervention Start Timing\n94\t0\n95\t5\n96\t10\n97\t15\n98\t20\n99\t25\n100\t30\n101\t35Attack Success Rate (%)\n102\tT op-K\n103\tSafeBeam\n104\tFigure 1.Attack success rate of the resultingbase modelsas we vary the time at which we introduce safety pretraining interventions. For\n105\tstandard inference (Top-K), we report the shaded region as the standard deviation computed over 5 seeds. When using SafeBeam, the\n106\tresults are deterministic. Introducing safety pretraining interventions during the middle of training leads to the highest level of safety\n107\tunder standard inference. SafeBeam benefits from interventions being introduced at the start of pretraining.\n108\ting. This leads to various amounts of safety interventions\n109\ttoken observed during pretraining. Our experiments are\n110\trun in the setting of pretraining a 1.7B parameter language\n111\tmodel with the SmolLM2 architecture (Allal et al., 2025),\n112\ton a pretraining mixture containing FineWeb-Edu (Penedo\n113\tet al., 2024), math, code, and other synthetic datasets (Allal\n114\tet al., 2025). To evaluate how intervention timing affects\n115\tsafety, we analyze the resulting models at multiple stages\n116\t(base models, instruction-tuned models, and models after\n117\tbenign finetuning). We also study two common deployment\n118\tchoices: (a) standard top-kdecoding, and (b) safety-aware\n119\tinference enabled by metadata. These settings prioritize\n120\tdifferent properties (robustness vs steerability), so the best\n121\tintervention timing differs.\n122\tWe find that the most effective start time depends on the\n123\tevaluation setting and inference procedure. Under stan-\n124\tdard top-kdecoding, introducing interventions after some\n125\tinitial safe-only pretraining (after 20%–60%) often yields\n126\tthe safest base and instruction-tuned models, and provides\n127\tthe strongest robustness after benign finetuning. In con-\n128\ttrast, when using a safety-aware inference-time algorithm\n129\t(SafeBeam), starting interventions from the beginning yields\n130\tthe most steerability toward safer generations. This is com-\n131\tplemented by our representation analysis: introducing in-\n132\tterventions earlier makes safe vs harmful examples more\n133\tlinearly separable in the final-layer representation space,\n134\tespecially when metadata is included. Finally, we find that\n135\tintervening after an initial safe-only phase (20% or 60%) im-\n136\tproves robustness to adversarial jailbreaks learned via GCG\n137\t(Zou et al., 2023), when compared to performing fully safe-\n138\tonly pretraining (100%) and safety interventions applied\n139\tfrom the start (0%). Overall, our results highlight curricu-\n140\tlum timing as a key design choice: early starts improve\n141\tsteerability under safety-aware inference, while delayed\n142\tstarts can improve robustness under standard decoding and\n143\tpost-benign finetuning evaluation.\n144\t2. Related Work\n145\tPretraining SafetyMost language model pretraining em-\n146\tploys simple heuristic filters that remove a small amount of\n147\tharmful content, such as from particular URLs or explicit\n148\tprofanity (Raffel et al., 2020; Xue, 2020). One early work\n149\tstudied the role of human preferences in language model\n150\tpretraining (Korbak et al., 2023), finding that it yields lower\n151\ttoxicity scores relative to finetuned models (on the 100M\n152\tparameter scale). Other works have taken a more explicit\n153\tdata curation approach. More recently, works have studied\n154\theuristic filtering based on educational content (Gunasekar\n155\tet al., 2023; Penedo et al., 2024), which also correlates with\n156\t(lower levels of) toxicity. Yet, Vidgen et al. (2024) note that\n157\tharmful examples remain even in these educational datasets.\n158\tAs such, some work explores the impacts of filtering unsafe\n159\tcontent from the pretraining corpus, training only on safe\n160\texamples (Li et al., 2025; O’Brien et al., 2025). Most re-\n161\tcently and relatedly, the work of Maini et al. (2025) studies\n162\tthe role of synthetic data generation to improve levels of\n163\tsafety in pretraining examples, while still retaining as much\n164\tinformation as possible, finding large improvements in ro-\n165\t2\n166\t\n167\tWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n168\t0% 20% 60% 100%\n169\tPretraining Intervention Start Timing\n170\t0\n171\t10\n172\t20\n173\t30\n174\t40\n175\t50\n176\t60Attack Success Rate (%)\n177\tT op-K\n178\tSafeBeam\n179\tFigure 2.Attack success rate of the resultingbenign finetuned models on math data(GSM8k) as we vary the time at which we introduce\n180\tsafety pretraining interventions. For standard inference (Top-K), we report the shaded region as the standard deviation computed over 5\n181\tseeds. When using SafeBeam, the results are deterministic. The SafeBeam performance is safest when interventions are introduced during\n182\tthe beginning of pretraining. Standard inference benefits from introducing safety interventions early (i.e., 0% or 20%) during pretraining.\n183\tbustness after a round of benign finetuning. We expand upon\n184\tthis work to study the question of when such interventions\n185\tshould be deployed during pretraining.\n186\tCurriculum LearningCurriculum learning studies how\n187\tthe order and composition of training data shape general-\n188\tization. Early work argues for presenting examples in a\n189\tprogression (e.g., from simpler to harder), and for adapt-\n190\ting the sampling policy as training proceeds (Bengio et al.,\n191\t2009; Graves et al., 2017). Such approaches have led to suc-\n192\tcess in various settings, such as question-answering (Sachan\n193\tand Xing, 2016) or reinforcement learning (Zhang et al.,\n194\t2020). Other work has explored when and what types of\n195\tcertain curriculum learning strategies work, demonstrated\n196\ton small-scale image classification tasks (Wu et al., 2021).\n197\tProgress in the language model pretraining realm has been\n198\trelatively static, likely due to the difficulty in measuring the\n199\thardness (Abdin et al., 2024) and similarity of content (Sam\n200\tet al., 2025a), as well as the computational demands.\n201\tStages of Language Model PretrainingIn large-scale\n202\tlanguage pretraining, most practical curricula have focused\n203\ton adjusting mixture weights over data sources rather than\n204\ttoken-level difficulty, largely due to computational com-\n205\tplexity. For example, optimizing source mixtures during\n206\tpretraining can yield gains in downstream performance and\n207\tstability (Xie et al., 2023), and a line of work explores\n208\tadaptive sampling or stage-specific mixtures that emphasize\n209\tmore useful distributions as training evolves (Jiang et al.,\n210\t2024; Ye et al., 2025).\n211\tComplementary results in a more coarse-grained setting\n212\tsuggest that pretraining in distinct stages can change what\n213\tmodels retain and how they transfer (Blakeney et al., 2024).\n214\tOur study is aligned with this perspective but targets a safety-\n215\tspecific question: instead of asking which domains to up-\n216\tweight, we varywhensafety-augmented data enters pre-\n217\ttraining. This allows us to measure whether safety signals\n218\tintroduced earlier versus later have a greater impact.\n219\t3. Curricula for Safety\n220\tThis section formalizes our notion of a safety curriculum,\n221\tdetailing the particular interventions and how/when they are\n222\tincorporated into the pretraining process.\n223\t3.1. Safety Pretraining Interventions\n224\tCrucial to this work are safety interventions that can be ex-\n225\tplored during the pretraining process, which are introduced\n226\tin the work of Maini et al. (2025). We briefly introduce and\n227\tdescribe these various pretraining interventions below.\n228\tContextualized RephrasingFor pretraining examples\n229\tthat contain harmful content or instructions, the example is\n230\trewritten to preserve useful factual or domain knowledge\n231\twhile explicitly providing context that frames the material as\n232\trisky or inappropriate to execute. The rewritten passages de-\n233\tscribe why the behavior is unsafe, when it is permissible to\n234\tdiscuss at a high level, and how to redirect toward safer gen-\n235\terations. The goal is to retain conceptual coverage (so the\n236\t3\n237\t\n238\tWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n239\t0% 20% 60% 100%\n240\tPretraining Intervention Start Timing\n241\t0\n242\t1\n243\t2\n244\t3\n245\t4\n246\t5\n247\t6Attack Success Rate (%)\n248\tT op-K\n249\tSafeBeam\n250\tFigure 3.Attack success rate of the resultinginstruction-tuned modelsas we vary the time at which we introduce safety pretraining\n251\tinterventions. For standard inference (Top-K), we report the shaded region as the standard deviation computed over 5 seeds. When\n252\tusing SafeBeam, the results are deterministic. We find that introducing interventions during the middle of pretraining leads to the safest\n253\tperformance with standard inference, and introducing interventions at the beginning leads to the safest performance when using SafeBeam.\n254\tmodel “knows about” the topic) while discouraging unsafe\n255\texecution, all within the same pretraining objective. Such\n256\texamples are rephrased with a LLaMA3.1 8B parameter\n257\tmodel (Touvron et al., 2023).\n258\tRefusal TrainingThe most harmful pretraining exam-\n259\tples are converted with a similar synthetic data pipeline\n260\tinto conversation-style request and refusal pairs to incor-\n261\tporate throughout pretraining. Prompts that elicit harmful\n262\tactions are paired with refusals that model helpful-but-safe\n263\tbehavior: declining the request, briefly explaining safety\n264\trationales, and, when appropriate, offering a safe alternative\n265\tor high-level guidance. These pairs are added directly to\n266\tthe pretraining corpus so that refusal behavior is learned\n267\tnatively to the model throughout pretraining, rather than\n268\tonly during a post-hoc alignment phase. This strengthens\n269\trobustness towards downstream finetuning, where refusal\n270\tbehavior can easily be eroded either on benign or explicitly\n271\tharmful tasks (Qi et al., 2024a; Betley et al., 2025).\n272\tMetadata-annotated Pretraining and SafeBeam\n273\tExamples are flagged with a special token (e.g.,\n274\t“<potentially unsafe content>”), which in-\n275\tdicates that a pretraining example is harmful. As with\n276\tthe other interventions, this is implemented as ordinary\n277\ttext (randomly inserted with a 5% chance at each of the\n278\ttoken positions of the pretraining example) that the model\n279\tpredicts, avoiding changes to the training loss. These\n280\tmetadata annotations build associations within the model\n281\tof harmful content and the special token, which enables\n282\tsteerability during inference-time. Specifically, this enables\n283\ta SafeBeam search algorithm, which is a safety-focused\n284\tinference-time modification. This modifies a standard beam\n285\tsearch algorithm by dropping candidate beams that have a\n286\thigh probability of the next token being the harmful special\n287\ttoken, leading to safer generations. The ultimate goal of\n288\tsuch an intervention is to steer the model towards safer and\n289\thigh-quality completions (Yuan et al., 2025).\n290\tWe adopt the same resulting datasets from applying these\n291\tinterventions on the FineWeb dataset (Penedo et al., 2024)\n292\tand other components of the SmolLM2 pretraining corpus\n293\t(Allal et al., 2025).\n294\t3.2. Safety Curricula\n295\tA central question of this work is how the timing of safety\n296\tinterventions during pretraining shapes downstream robust-\n297\tness. Prior work on safety pretraining (Maini et al., 2025)\n298\thas introduced interventions from the very start of training—\n299\teffectively modifying the full corpus before pretraining be-\n300\tgins. Other work has demonstrated that orderings of certain"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_012AYThVbkNwud8D2jBMAa8T","session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"426ff156-7e05-45aa-bd5e-1bb82c1ba032","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:20:46.360Z"}
