{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NVsLYHCzyzJ5Ub2Q8w28Hg","type":"tool_result","content":"300\tgins. Other work has demonstrated that orderings of certain\n301\tconcepts can improve the speed of learning (Chen et al.,\n302\t2023). Similarly, in the human learning process, we often\n303\tfirst learn about general knowledge, such as language and\n304\tarithmetic, before addressing potentially harmful or contro-\n305\tversial content, such as wars and tragedies. At the other\n306\textreme, filtering approaches (O’Brien et al., 2025) that per-\n307\tmanently and completely remove all harmful content during\n308\tpretraining potentially lose too many capabilities from the\n309\tunderlying model. We adopt a similar approach here, where\n310\t4\n311\t\n312\tWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n313\tTable 1.Capability evaluation results across intervention start timings.We report accuracy on standard benchmarks: ARC-Challenge,\n314\tCommonsenseQA (CS-QA), GSM8K, OpenBookQA, PIQA, TriviaQA, and Winogrande. We observe no obvious degradations in\n315\tcapabilities as we include safety pretraining interventions earlier (exposing models to more safety pretraining data); in fact, earlier\n316\tpretraining interventions seem to lead to higher levels of capabilities.\n317\tIntervention Avg. ARC-C CS-QA GSM8K OpenBookQA PIQA TriviaQA Wino.\n318\t0% 37.2% 42.9% 19.7% 7.4% 42.6% 76.6% 12.7% 58.8%\n319\t20% 36.7% 43.5% 22.9% 6.1% 39.8% 76.0% 10.0% 58.7%\n320\t60% 35.6% 41.8% 21.1% 5.5% 41.6% 75.1% 5.8% 58.0%\n321\t100% 36.1% 42.9% 21.6% 4.9% 42.8% 75.1% 6.0% 59.4%\n322\twe study a curriculum of first pretraining for a phase on\n323\tsafe-only data, before introducing safety interventions af-\n324\tter a certain percentage of tokens of the full 600B token\n325\tpretraining budget.\n326\tTo study the role of thetimingof introducing safety inter-\n327\tventions, we study 4 main settings. The first setting (0%)\n328\tapplies interventions from the very beginning, which di-\n329\trectly mirrors the setup in prior Safety Pretraining work\n330\t(Maini et al., 2025). This captures no pretraining phase on\n331\tsafe-only data. The second setting (20%) delays interven-\n332\ttions until after the model has already seen a substantial\n333\tportion of “safe” general web-scale data, allowing it to ac-\n334\tquire broad linguistic and factual knowledge before any\n335\tsafety interventions. The third setting (60%) introduces in-\n336\tterventions only in the later stages of training, when much of\n337\tthe model’s base distribution of language has already been\n338\testablished. Finally, the last setting (100%) corresponds to\n339\tfully training on safe-only data, which is equivalent to prior\n340\twork that filters out all unsafe content (O’Brien et al., 2025).\n341\tTo also vary the types of interventions employed, we explore\n342\tthe two primary settings from Safety Pretraining (Maini\n343\tet al., 2025): (i) we first study using all of the interven-\n344\ttions in conjunction, including the metadata tagging and\n345\tinference-time modifications, (ii) using only rephrasing and\n346\trefusal training without any metadata tagging. The second\n347\tset of experiments here considers a slightly less aggressive\n348\tmodification to pretraining, only in terms of data curation.\n349\t4. Experiments\n350\tTo evaluate the impacts of the timing of safety curricula, we\n351\tadopt evaluations along multiple axes of the model pipeline.\n352\tOur evaluations include safety (of base model, instruction-\n353\ttuned models, and finetuned models), helpfulness on harm-\n354\tless and benign queries, jailbreakability through adversarial\n355\tsuffixes, and in analyzing model internals and the underly-\n356\ting representation space.\n357\t4.1. Safety Evaluations\n358\tWe follow the work of Maini et al. (2025), performing safety\n359\tevaluations at 3 main stages: (i) base model – immediately\n360\tafter pretraining, (ii) instruction-tuned models – after a stan-\n361\tdardized post-training setup, and (iii) benign finetuned mod-\n362\tels – after a round of benign finetuning on math data, e.g.,\n363\tGSM8K (Cobbe et al., 2021).\n364\tWe first evaluate the safety of our models immediately after\n365\tpretraining. We use the completion-style harmful request\n366\tbenchmark from Maini et al. (2025). This evaluates the\n367\ttendencies of the base models to complete the beginning\n368\tof a harmful prompt. Next, we evaluate the models af-\n369\tter performing a standard instruction tuning recipe, which\n370\talso includes some safety training and refusal examples.\n371\tOur evaluation is comprised of 4 standard safety bench-\n372\tmarks: HarmBench (Mazeika et al., 2024), TDC (Mal-\n373\toyan et al., 2024), JailbreakBench (Chao et al., 2024),\n374\tAdvBench (Zou et al., 2023). We also incorporate a harder\n375\tevaluation setting that incorporates adversarial jailbreaking,\n376\twhere we learn adversarial suffixes via the GCG algorithm\n377\t(Zou et al., 2023) that are optimized on each model to in-\n378\tcrease the rate of compliance with harmful requests.\n379\tFinally, we evaluate the models after an epoch of benign,\n380\tsupervised finetuning on a helpful, non-adversarial dataset\n381\tof GSM8K (Cobbe et al., 2021), which is common practice\n382\tfor mathematical reasoning, without any focus on safety or\n383\talignment. Despite this being non-adversarial data, other\n384\tworks have demonstrated that such rounds of supervised\n385\tfinetuning can erode aligned behaviors (Qi et al., 2024a;\n386\tBetley et al., 2025).\n387\t4.2. Capability and Helpfulness Evaluations\n388\tWhen introducing safety interventions that may increase\n389\trefusal rates, it is crucial to assess any impact on model\n390\tcapabilities and helpfulness. For capabilities, we evaluate\n391\ton a suite of standard benchmarks spanning general knowl-\n392\tedge (ARC-Challenge, TriviaQA), commonsense reasoning\n393\t(CommonsenseQA, OpenBookQA, PIQA, Winogrande),\n394\tand mathematical reasoning (GSM8K). Additional experi-\n395\tment details are deferred to Appendix B.\n396\t5\n397\t\n398\tWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n399\t0 50 100 150 200 250 300\n400\tCount\n401\t0%\n402\t20%\n403\t60%\n404\t100%Pretraining Intervention Timing\n405\tCompliant & Helpful\n406\tCompliant & Unhelpful\n407\tPartial Refusal Full Refusal\n408\tFigure 4.Comparison of overrefusal rates on Alpaca (Taori et al., 2023) when using standard (Top-k) sampling for inference. We find that\n409\tincorporating interventions earlier during pretraining leads to a better compliance rate on benign requests.\n410\tTo measure helpfulness, we evaluate model compliance\n411\ton benign requests from the Alpaca dataset (Taori et al.,\n412\t2023). We use GPT-4o-mini as a judge to classify each\n413\tresponse into one of four categories: (1) compliant and\n414\thelpful, (2) compliant but unhelpful, (3) partial refusal, or\n415\t(4) full refusal. Categories (1) and (2) represent desirable\n416\tcompliance behavior, while categories (3) and (4) indicate\n417\toverrefusal. For models using the SafeBeam algorithm,\n418\twe additionally introduce a fifth category: (5) shortcircuit,\n419\twhich occurs when generation terminates upon producing\n420\tthe harmful metadata token. In practice, such responses can\n421\tbe post-processed at serving time by substituting a default\n422\trefusal message from a set of known safe completions.\n423\t4.3. Representation Analysis\n424\tTo analyze the impact of various curricula on the underlying\n425\trepresentation space of our models, we evaluate the sepa-\n426\trability of safe vs harmful content. We train linear probes\n427\tto classify between examples from FineWeb data that have\n428\tbeen annotated as safe versus unsafe, learned over the repre-\n429\tsentations taken from the internal activations of the model’s\n430\tfinal layer. For the safety label, we use the safety score from\n431\tMaini et al. (2025), which is produced by GPT-4o-mini that\n432\tjudges pretraining examples with a safety rubric.\n433\t4.4. Training Details\n434\tPretraining SetupFor our experiments, we adopt the\n435\tsame setup of the SmolLM2 (Allal et al., 2025) for\n436\tall our experiments. We train 1.7B parameter lan-\n437\tguage models with a pretraining corpus of a mixture\n438\tof FineWeb-Edu, StackOverflow, FineMath, and\n439\tCosmopedia. For our safety pretraining interventions,\n440\twe adopt the modified datasets of SafeWeb, RefuseWeb,\n441\tand MoralEducation from Maini et al. (2025), which\n442\tare safety-focused, rephrased and recontextualized versions\n443\tof harmful pretraining examples fromFineWeb-Edu.\n444\tPretraining is performed using LitGPT (AI, 2023), with\n445\tFlashAttention-2 enabled and mixed-precision training for\n446\tefficiency. We use the same hyperparameters (e.g., learning\n447\trate schedule, batch size, and sequence length) as in the\n448\tSmolLM2 pretraining setup.\n449\tPost-training SetupFor a standardized post-training\n450\tstack, we use a combination of Ultrachat-200k\n451\twith AllenAI WildGuardMix and WildJailbreak\n452\tdatasets for safety instruction tuning. This follows standard\n453\tpractice from prior works in safety training (Zou et al., 2024;\n454\tMaini et al., 2025).\n455\t5. Results\n456\tWe now present our findings on how safety curricula influ-\n457\tence robustness, helpfulness, and internal representations.\n458\t5.1. Safety Results\n459\tBase ModelsTiming matters even before instruction tun-\n460\ting (Figure 1). Under standard top-k sampling, introducing\n461\tinterventions in the middle of pretraining (20% or 60%)\n462\tyields the safest base models, while training on safe-only\n463\tdata (100%) is the least safe. This again complements the\n464\tfindings from prior work (Li et al., 2025; Maini et al., 2025).\n465\tIn contrast, with SafeBeam, incorporating interventions and\n466\tmetadata from the start (0%) provides measurable gains.\n467\tInstruction-tuned ModelsA similar pattern holds with\n468\tthe models that have undergone instruction tuning (Fig-\n469\ture 3). Models trained with interventions during the middle\n470\t6\n471\t\n472\tWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n473\t0% 20% 60% 100%\n474\tPretraining Intervention Start Timing\n475\t0\n476\t10\n477\t20\n478\t30\n479\t40\n480\t50\n481\t60Attack Success Rate (%)\n482\tT op-K\n483\tSafeBeam\n484\tFigure 5.Jailbreakability of our models via the GCG algorithm (Zou et al., 2023) as we vary the timing of safety pretraining interventions.\n485\tWe find that introducing interventions during the middle stages of pretraining greatly improves the steerability of models towards safe\n486\tcompletions and refusals when exposed to adversarially learned suffixes.\n487\tof pretraining exhibit stronger safety performance under\n488\ttop-kinference than those with no interventions. Again,\n489\tSafeBeam benefits the most when metadata is incorporated\n490\tfrom the beginning (i.e., 0%).\n491\tBenign Finetuned ModelsThe clearest and most notice-\n492\table effects emerge in our evaluation setting after a benign\n493\tfinetune on mathematical data (Figure 2). Here, SafeBeam\n494\tachieves the greatest robustness when interventions are in-\n495\tcluded from the very start of pretraining. For standard top-k\n496\tdecoding, introducing interventions after roughly 20% of\n497\ttraining yields the strongest post-finetuning safety.\n498\tTaken together, our evaluations suggest two main takeaways.\n499\tFirst, when using modified SafeBeam inference, introducing\n500\tmetadata-annotated unsafe data earliest in pretraining leads\n501\tto the best steerability towards safer completions. Secondly,\n502\twith top-k inference, introducing safety pretraining interven-\n503\ttions during the middle of training (after 20% or 60%) leads\n504\tto the most robust performance. This suggests that allowing\n505\tthe model to first absorb general-purpose safe data before\n506\tapplying any safety interventions may produce alignment\n507\tthat is more robust to subsequent benign finetuning.\n508\t5.2. Capability Results\n509\tWe evaluate whether safety pretraining interventions de-\n510\tgrade general model capabilities across various standard\n511\tbenchmarks (Table 1). Overall, we find that safety inter-\n512\tventions introduce minimal capability trade-offs and, in\n513\tsome cases, may even improve performance. We attribute\n514\tthis to the model’s efficient learning from high-quality syn-\n515\tthetic data (Maini et al., 2024). Taken together, these re-\n516\tsults indicate that safety pretraining interventions do not\n517\tmeaningfully degrade model capabilities; indeed, earlier\n518\tinterventions appear mildly beneficial on average.\n519\t5.3. Overrefusal Results\n520\tWe assess the impact of pretraining interventions on model\n521\thelpfulness using benign requests from the Alpaca bench-\n522\tmark (Taori et al., 2023). Under standard top- k sampling\n523\t(Figure 4), incorporating interventions earlier during pre-\n524\ttraining (0% or 20%) yields a slight improvement in com-\n525\tpliance rates. These results suggest that safety pretraining\n526\tinterventions introduce minimal trade-offs in overrefusal\n527\tbehavior under standard inference.\n528\tWhen using the SafeBeam algorithm (Figure 9), we ob-\n529\tserve a more nuanced pattern: earlier interventions produce\n530\tmodestly higher overrefusal rates, yet the quality of com-\n531\tpliant responses improves. The figure reveals that earlier\n532\tpretraining interventions (0% and 20%) increase the frac-\n533\ttion of compliant-and-helpful responses among non-refused\n534\toutputs, even as overall refusal rates rise slightly. We hy-\n535\tpothesize that this reflects improved calibration: early inter-\n536\tventions strengthen the correspondence between the harm-\n537\tful metadata tag and genuinely unsafe content, enabling\n538\tSafeBeam to filter more precisely. The surviving beams\n539\tthus tend to produce higher-quality completions.\n540\t7\n541\t\n542\tWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n543\t0% 20% 60% 100%\n544\tSafety Pretraining Intervention Timing\n545\t0.785\n546\t0.790\n547\t0.795\n548\t0.800\n549\t0.805\n550\t0.810\n551\t0.815Separability AUC\n552\tWith Metadata\n553\tWithout Metadata\n554\t0% 20% 60% 100%\n555\tSafety Pretraining Intervention Timing\n556\t0.790\n557\t0.795\n558\t0.800\n559\t0.805\n560\t0.810\n561\t0.815\n562\t0.820\n563\t0.825Separability AUC\n564\tWith Metadata\n565\tWithout Metadata\n566\tFigure 6.Separability of safe vs unsafe content (as annotated by GPT-4o-mini) in thelast layer representation spaceof base models\n567\t(Left) and instruction-tuned models (Right), as we vary the start timing when we incorporate safety pretraining interventions. We find that\n568\tintroducing interventions earlier yields greater separability in representation space(especially with the incorporation of harmful\n569\tmetadata tags). The shaded regions denote the standard deviation computed over 5 training runs.\n570\t5.4. Jailbreaking Results\n571\tWe also present results on how susceptible our models are\n572\tto jailbreaking attacks using the GCG algorithm (Zou et al.,\n573\t2023), as we vary the timing of the safety pretraining inter-\n574\tventions. Surprisingly, we find that introducing pretraining\n575\tinterventions after some initial safe-only pretraining (i.e.,\n576\tat 20% or at 60%) leads tosignificantly more robustness\n577\tto jailbreaks via GCG when using the SafeBeam inference\n578\talgorithm (Figure 5). On the other hand, we find that jail-\n579\tbreakability under standard inference does not noticeably\n580\tchange given different intervention timings.\n581\t5.5. Representation Results\n582\tIn settings without harmful metadata tags, earlier interven-\n583\ttions slightly improve the separability of safe versus unsafe\n584\tpoints (with a linear classifier over the last-layer activations).\n585\tWhen metadata is included, the effect is more pronounced:\n586\tintroducing interventions from the start yields the highest\n587\tlinear-probe AUC, suggesting a much cleaner separation of\n588\tharmful and safe content in the representation space. This\n589\talso supports the improved SafeBeam robustness, where\n590\tmodels are more steerable towards safer responses when\n591\tinterventions are included early in pretraining.\n592\t6. Discussion\n593\tOur work studies the role of different safety curricula, or\n594\thow the timing of safety pretraining interventions (e.g.,\n595\twhen and how safety-augmented data enters pretraining) im-\n596\tpacts the robustness of our models. Our experiments show\n597\tthat incorporating safety pretraining interventions indeed\n598\thelp, but the best timing depends on the setting: delayed\n599\tinterventions (e.g., 20%–60%) can yield stronger robustness\n600\tunder standard decoding and against adversarial jailbreaks,\n601\twhile early interventions (0%) improve steerability under\n602\tsafety-aware inference (SafeBeam) and yield clearer separa-\n603\ttion of safe vs unsafe content in representation space. Taken\n604\ttogether, these findings highlight how the timing of safety\n605\tinterventions is an important choice in shaping a model’s\n606\tbehavior, offering guidance for building more trustworthy\n607\tand responsible language models.\n608\tWhy does timing matter?While our experiments estab-\n609\tlish that intervention timing significantly affects outcomes,\n610\tunderstanding the underlying mechanisms remains an open\n611\tquestion. We offer several hypotheses for future inves-\n612\ttigation. For standard top-k decoding, delayed interven-\n613\ttions (20%-60%) may succeed because the model benefits\n614\tfrom first acquiring general linguistic competence and world\n615\tknowledge before safety signals are introduced. Early safety\n616\tinterventions might compete with or interfere with learn-\n617\ting basic representations, potentially causing the model to\n618\tdevelop shallow safety heuristics rather than robust under-\n619\tstanding. By contrast, when the model has already formed\n620\tstable representations of language and concepts, safety in-\n621\tterventions may integrate more deeply into these existing\n622\tstructures, making them harder to remove through subse-\n623\tquent finetuning.\n624\tFor SafeBeam inference, early interventions may help be-\n625\tcause the metadata-based steering mechanism relies on\n626\tstrong, well-calibrated associations between the harmful\n627\tcontent tag and genuinely unsafe material. Introducing these\n628\tassociations from the start of training allows them to be re-\n629\tinforced throughout the entire pretraining process, resulting\n630\tin more reliable probability estimates that SafeBeam can ex-\n631\tploit. This interpretation is supported by our representation\n632\tanalysis (Figure 6), which shows that early interventions\n633\twith metadata yield the cleanest separation between safe\n634\tand unsafe content in representation space.\n635\tA limitation of our study is that the introduction of safety\n636\t8\n637\t\n638\tWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n639\tpretraining interventions at different times during pretrain-\n640\ting means that certain models have seen more synthetic con-\n641\ttextualized data or refusal data. However, we note our main\n642\teffects arenot monotonicin the number of intervention\n643\ttokens (i.e., “more intervention tokens” do not consistently\n644\tyield safer models), suggesting thatwhensafety-augmented\n645\tdata is introduced matters beyond total quantity.\n646\t9\n647\t\n648\tWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n649\tReferences"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_012AYThVbkNwud8D2jBMAa8T","session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"239eea86-ad23-4992-be64-80efb493de59","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:20:48.902Z"}
