{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01UMQApBshvBNGohcVWSL6np","type":"tool_result","content":"650\tMarah Abdin, Jyoti Aneja, Hany Awadalla, Ahmed Awadal-\n651\tlah, Ammar Ahmad Awan, Nguyen Bach, Amit Bahree,\n652\tArash Bakhtiari, Jianmin Bao, Harkirat Behl, et al. Phi-3\n653\ttechnical report: A highly capable language model locally\n654\ton your phone.arXiv preprint arXiv:2404.14219, 2024.\n655\tLightning AI. Litgpt. https://github.com/\n656\tLightning-AI/litgpt, 2023.\n657\tLoubna Ben Allal, Anton Lozhkov, Elie Bakouch,\n658\tGabriel Mart´ın Bl´azquez, Guilherme Penedo, Lewis Tun-\n659\tstall, Andr ´es Marafioti, Hynek Kydl ´ıˇcek, Agust ´ın Pi-\n660\tqueres Lajar´ın, Vaibhav Srivastav, Joshua Lochner, Caleb\n661\tFahlgren, Xuan-Son Nguyen, Cl´ementine Fourrier, Ben\n662\tBurtenshaw, Hugo Larcher, Haojun Zhao, Cyril Zakka,\n663\tMathieu Morlon, Colin Raffel, Leandro von Werra, and\n664\tThomas Wolf. Smollm2: When smol goes big – data-\n665\tcentric training of a small language model, 2025. URL\n666\thttps://arxiv.org/abs/2502.02737.\n667\tMaksym Andriushchenko, Alexandra Souly, Mateusz\n668\tDziemian, Derek Duenas, Maxwell Lin, Justin Wang,\n669\tDan Hendrycks, Andy Zou, J Zico Kolter, Matt Fredrik-\n670\tson, Yarin Gal, and Xander Davies. Agentharm: A bench-\n671\tmark for measuring harmfulness of LLM agents. In\n672\tThe Thirteenth International Conference on Learning\n673\tRepresentations, 2025. URL https://openreview.\n674\tnet/forum?id=AC5n7xHuR1.\n675\tYuntao Bai, Saurav Kadavath, Sandipan Kundu, Amanda\n676\tAskell, Jackson Kernion, Andy Jones, Anna Chen, Anna\n677\tGoldie, Azalia Mirhoseini, Cameron McKinnon, et al.\n678\tConstitutional ai: Harmlessness from ai feedback.arXiv\n679\tpreprint arXiv:2212.08073, 2022.\n680\tYoshua Bengio, J´erˆome Louradour, Ronan Collobert, and\n681\tJason Weston. Curriculum learning. InProceedings\n682\tof the 26th annual international conference on machine\n683\tlearning, pages 41–48, 2009.\n684\tJan Betley, Daniel Tan, Niels Warncke, Anna Sztyber-\n685\tBetley, Xuchan Bao, Mart´ın Soto, Nathan Labenz, and\n686\tOwain Evans. Emergent misalignment: Narrow finetun-\n687\ting can produce broadly misaligned llms.arXiv preprint\n688\tarXiv:2502.17424, 2025.\n689\tCody Blakeney, Mansheej Paul, Brett W. Larsen, Sean\n690\tOwen, and Jonathan Frankle. Does your data spark joy?\n691\tperformance gains from domain upsampling at the end\n692\tof training. InFirst Conference on Language Modeling,\n693\t2024. URL https://openreview.net/forum?\n694\tid=vwIIAot0ff.\n695\tYewon Byun, Shantanu Gupta, Zachary C Lipton,\n696\tRachel Leah Childers, and Bryan Wilder. Using imper-\n697\tfect synthetic data in downstream inference tasks.arXiv\n698\tpreprint arXiv:2508.06635, 2025.\n699\tPatrick Chao, Alexander Robey, Edgar Dobriban, Hamed\n700\tHassani, George J Pappas, and Eric Wong. Jailbreaking\n701\tblack box large language models in twenty queries.arXiv\n702\tpreprint arXiv:2310.08419, 2023.\n703\tPatrick Chao, Edoardo Debenedetti, Alexander Robey,\n704\tMaksym Andriushchenko, Francesco Croce, Vikash Se-\n705\thwag, Edgar Dobriban, Nicolas Flammarion, George J\n706\tPappas, Florian Tram`er, et al. Jailbreakbench: An open\n707\trobustness benchmark for jailbreaking large language\n708\tmodels. InConference on Neural Information Processing\n709\tSystems (NeurIPS), 2024.\n710\tMayee Chen, Nicholas Roberts, Kush Bhatia, Jue Wang,\n711\tCe Zhang, Frederic Sala, and Christopher R´e. Skill-it! a\n712\tdata-driven skills framework for understanding and train-\n713\ting language models.Advances in Neural Information\n714\tProcessing Systems, 36:36000–36040, 2023.\n715\tKarl Cobbe, Vineet Kosaraju, Mohammad Bavarian, Mark\n716\tChen, Heewoo Jun, Lukasz Kaiser, Matthias Plappert,\n717\tJerry Tworek, Jacob Hilton, Reiichiro Nakano, et al.\n718\tTraining verifiers to solve math word problems.arXiv\n719\tpreprint arXiv:2110.14168, 2021.\n720\tRoya Firoozi, Johnathan Tucker, Stephen Tian, Anirudha\n721\tMajumdar, Jiankai Sun, Weiyu Liu, Yuke Zhu, Shuran\n722\tSong, Ashish Kapoor, Karol Hausman, et al. Foundation\n723\tmodels in robotics: Applications, challenges, and the\n724\tfuture.The International Journal of Robotics Research,\n725\t44(5):701–739, 2025.\n726\tLeo Gao, Jonathan Tow, Baber Abbasi, Stella Biderman,\n727\tSid Black, Anthony DiPofi, Charles Foster, Laurence\n728\tGolding, Jeffrey Hsu, Alain Le Noac’h, Haonan Li,\n729\tKyle McDonell, Niklas Muennighoff, Chris Ociepa, Ja-\n730\tson Phang, Laria Reynolds, Hailey Schoelkopf, Aviya\n731\tSkowron, Lintang Sutawika, Eric Tang, Anish Thite,\n732\tBen Wang, Kevin Wang, and Andy Zou. The lan-\n733\tguage model evaluation harness, 07 2024. URL https:\n734\t//zenodo.org/records/12608602.\n735\tAlex Graves, Marc G Bellemare, Jacob Menick, Remi\n736\tMunos, and Koray Kavukcuoglu. Automated curriculum\n737\tlearning for neural networks. Ininternational conference\n738\ton machine learning, pages 1311–1320. Pmlr, 2017.\n739\tSuriya Gunasekar, Yi Zhang, Jyoti Aneja, Caio\n740\tC´esar Teodoro Mendes, Allie Del Giorno, Sivakanth\n741\tGopi, Mojan Javaheripi, Piero Kauffmann, Gustavo\n742\tde Rosa, Olli Saarikivi, et al. Textbooks are all you\n743\tneed.arXiv preprint arXiv:2306.11644, 2023.\n744\tYiding Jiang, Allan Zhou, Zhili Feng, Sadhika Malladi,\n745\tand J Zico Kolter. Adaptive data optimization: Dy-\n746\tnamic sample selection with scaling laws.arXiv preprint\n747\tarXiv:2410.11820, 2024.\n748\t10\n749\t\n750\tWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n751\tTomasz Korbak, Kejian Shi, Angelica Chen, Rasika\n752\tBhalerao, Christopher L Buckley, Jason Phang, Sam Bow-\n753\tman, and Ethan Perez. Pretraining language models with\n754\thuman preferences.arXiv preprint arXiv:2302.08582,\n755\t2023.\n756\tKenneth Li, Yida Chen, Fernanda Vi´egas, and Martin Wat-\n757\ttenberg. When bad data leads to good models. InF orty-\n758\tsecond International Conference on Machine Learning,\n759\t2025. URL https://openreview.net/forum?\n760\tid=SsLGTZKXf1.\n761\tNathaniel Li, Alexander Pan, Anjali Gopal, Summer Yue,\n762\tDaniel Berrios, Alice Gatti, Justin D Li, Ann-Kathrin\n763\tDombrowski, Shashwat Goel, Long Phan, et al. The\n764\twmdp benchmark: Measuring and reducing malicious\n765\tuse with unlearning.arXiv preprint arXiv:2403.03218,\n766\t2024.\n767\tValentin Li´evin, Christoffer Egeberg Hother, Andreas Geert\n768\tMotzfeldt, and Ole Winther. Can large language models\n769\treason about medical questions?Patterns, 5(3), 2024.\n770\tPratyush Maini, Skyler Seto, Richard Bai, David Grangier,\n771\tYizhe Zhang, and Navdeep Jaitly. Rephrasing the web: A\n772\trecipe for compute and data-efficient language modeling.\n773\tIn Lun-Wei Ku, Andre Martins, and Vivek Srikumar,\n774\teditors,Proceedings of the 62nd Annual Meeting of the\n775\tAssociation for Computational Linguistics (V olume 1:\n776\tLong Papers), pages 14044–14072, Bangkok, Thailand,\n777\tAugust 2024. Association for Computational Linguistics.\n778\tdoi: 10.18653/v1/2024.acl-long.757. URL https://\n779\taclanthology.org/2024.acl-long.757/.\n780\tPratyush Maini, Sachin Goyal, Dylan Sam, Alex Robey,\n781\tYash Savani, Yiding Jiang, Andy Zou, Zacharcy C Lipton,\n782\tand J Zico Kolter. Safety pretraining: Toward the next\n783\tgeneration of safe ai.arXiv preprint arXiv:2504.16980,\n784\t2025.\n785\tNarek Maloyan, Ekansh Verma, Bulat Nutfullin, and Bislan\n786\tAshinov. Trojan detection in large language models: In-\n787\tsights from the trojan detection challenge.arXiv preprint\n788\tarXiv:2404.13660, 2024.\n789\tMantas Mazeika, Long Phan, Xuwang Yin, Andy Zou, Zi-\n790\tfan Wang, Norman Mu, Elham Sakhaee, Nathaniel Li,\n791\tSteven Basart, Bo Li, David Forsyth, and Dan Hendrycks.\n792\tHarmbench: A standardized evaluation framework for\n793\tautomated red teaming and robust refusal.arXiv preprint\n794\tarXiv:2402.04249, 2024.\n795\tKyle O’Brien, Stephen Casper, Quentin Anthony, Tomek\n796\tKorbak, Robert Kirk, Xander Davies, Ishan Mishra, Ge-\n797\toffrey Irving, Yarin Gal, and Stella Biderman. Deep\n798\tignorance: Filtering pretraining data builds tamper-\n799\tresistant safeguards into open-weight llms.arXiv preprint\n800\tarXiv:2508.06601, 2025.\n801\tLong Ouyang, Jeffrey Wu, Xu Jiang, Diogo Almeida, Car-\n802\troll Wainwright, Pamela Mishkin, Chong Zhang, Sand-\n803\thini Agarwal, Katarina Slama, Alex Ray, et al. Training\n804\tlanguage models to follow instructions with human feed-\n805\tback.Advances in neural information processing systems,\n806\t35:27730–27744, 2022.\n807\tGuilherme Penedo, Hynek Kydl ´ıˇcek, Loubna Ben allal,\n808\tAnton Lozhkov, Margaret Mitchell, Colin Raffel, Lean-\n809\tdro V on Werra, and Thomas Wolf. The fineweb datasets:\n810\tDecanting the web for the finest text data at scale, 2024.\n811\tURLhttps://arxiv.org/abs/2406.17557.\n812\tXiangyu Qi, Ashwinee Panda, Kaifeng Lyu, Xiao Ma,\n813\tSubhrajit Roy, Ahmad Beirami, Prateek Mittal, and Peter\n814\tHenderson. Safety alignment should be made more than\n815\tjust a few tokens deep.arXiv preprint arXiv:2406.05946,\n816\t2024a.\n817\tXiangyu Qi, Ashwinee Panda, Kaifeng Lyu, Xiao Ma,\n818\tSubhrajit Roy, Ahmad Beirami, Prateek Mittal, and Pe-\n819\tter Henderson. Safety alignment should be made more\n820\tthan just a few tokens deep, 2024b. URL https:\n821\t//arxiv.org/abs/2406.05946.\n822\tRafael Rafailov, Archit Sharma, Eric Mitchell, Christo-\n823\tpher D Manning, Stefano Ermon, and Chelsea Finn. Di-\n824\trect preference optimization: Your language model is\n825\tsecretly a reward model.Advances in Neural Information\n826\tProcessing Systems, 36:53728–53741, 2023.\n827\tColin Raffel, Noam Shazeer, Adam Roberts, Katherine Lee,\n828\tSharan Narang, Michael Matena, Yanqi Zhou, Wei Li,\n829\tand Peter J Liu. Exploring the limits of transfer learning\n830\twith a unified text-to-text transformer.Journal of machine\n831\tlearning research, 21(140):1–67, 2020.\n832\tAlexander Robey, Zachary Ravichandran, Vijay Kumar,\n833\tHamed Hassani, and George J Pappas. Jailbreaking\n834\tllm-controlled robots.arXiv preprint arXiv:2410.13691,\n835\t2024.\n836\tMrinmaya Sachan and Eric Xing. Easy questions first? a\n837\tcase study on curriculum learning for question answering.\n838\tInProceedings of the 54th Annual Meeting of the Asso-\n839\tciation for Computational Linguistics (V olume 1: Long\n840\tPapers), pages 453–463, 2016.\n841\tDylan Sam, Ayan Chakrabarti, Afshin Rostamizadeh, Sriku-\n842\tmar Ramalingam, Gui Citovsky, and Sanjiv Kumar. Ana-\n843\tlyzing similarity metrics for data selection for language\n844\tmodel pretraining.arXiv preprint arXiv:2502.02494,\n845\t2025a.\n846\tDylan Sam, Marc Finzi, and J Zico Kolter. Predicting\n847\tthe performance of black-box llms through self-queries.\n848\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2501.01558, 2025b.\n849\t11\n850\t\n851\tWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n852\tDylan Sam, Alexander Robey, Andy Zou, Matt Fredrik-\n853\tson, and J Zico Kolter. Evaluating language model rea-\n854\tsoning about confidential information.arXiv preprint\n855\tarXiv:2508.19980, 2025c.\n856\tMrinank Sharma, Meg Tong, Jesse Mu, Jerry Wei, Jorrit\n857\tKruthoff, Scott Goodfriend, Euan Ong, Alwin Peng, Raj\n858\tAgarwal, Cem Anil, et al. Constitutional classifiers: De-\n859\tfending against universal jailbreaks across thousands of\n860\thours of red teaming.arXiv preprint arXiv:2501.18837,\n861\t2025.\n862\tRohan Taori, Ishaan Gulrajani, Tianyi Zhang, Yann Dubois,\n863\tXuechen Li, Carlos Guestrin, Percy Liang, and Tat-\n864\tsunori B Hashimoto. Stanford alpaca: An instruction-\n865\tfollowing llama model, 2023.\n866\tArun James Thirunavukarasu, Darren Shu Jeng Ting, Ka-\n867\tbilan Elangovan, Laura Gutierrez, Ting Fang Tan, and\n868\tDaniel Shu Wei Ting. Large language models in medicine.\n869\tNature medicine, 29(8):1930–1940, 2023.\n870\tHugo Touvron, Thibaut Lavril, Gautier Izacard, Xavier Mar-\n871\ttinet, Marie-Anne Lachaux, Timoth´ee Lacroix, Baptiste\n872\tRozi`ere, Naman Goyal, Eric Hambro, Faisal Azhar, et al.\n873\tLlama: Open and efficient foundation language models.\n874\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2302.13971, 2023.\n875\tAlexander Matt Turner, Lisa Thiergart, Gavin Leech, David\n876\tUdell, Juan J Vazquez, Ulisse Mini, and Monte MacDi-\n877\tarmid. Steering language models with activation engi-\n878\tneering.arXiv preprint arXiv:2308.10248, 2023.\n879\tBertie Vidgen, Adarsh Agrawal, Ahmed M Ahmed, Victor\n880\tAkinwande, Namir Al-Nuaimi, Najla Alfaraj, Elie Al-\n881\thajjar, Lora Aroyo, Trupti Bavalatti, Max Bartolo, et al.\n882\tIntroducing v0. 5 of the ai safety benchmark from mlcom-\n883\tmons.arXiv preprint arXiv:2404.12241, 2024.\n884\tXiaoxia Wu, Ethan Dyer, and Behnam Neyshabur. When do\n885\tcurricula work? InInternational Conference on Learning\n886\tRepresentations, 2021. URL https://openreview.\n887\tnet/forum?id=tW4QEInpni.\n888\tSang Michael Xie, Hieu Pham, Xuanyi Dong, Nan Du,\n889\tHanxiao Liu, Yifeng Lu, Percy S Liang, Quoc V Le,\n890\tTengyu Ma, and Adams Wei Yu. Doremi: Optimizing\n891\tdata mixtures speeds up language model pretraining.Ad-\n892\tvances in Neural Information Processing Systems, 36:\n893\t69798–69818, 2023.\n894\tL Xue. mt5: A massively multilingual pre-trained text-\n895\tto-text transformer.arXiv preprint arXiv:2010.11934,\n896\t2020.\n897\tJiasheng Ye, Peiju Liu, Tianxiang Sun, Jun Zhan, Yun-\n898\thua Zhou, and Xipeng Qiu. Data mixing laws: Opti-\n899\tmizing data mixtures by predicting language modeling\n900\tperformance. InThe Thirteenth International Confer-\n901\tence on Learning Representations, 2025. URL https:\n902\t//openreview.net/forum?id=jjCB27TMK3.\n903\tYuan Yuan, Tina Sriskandarajah, Anna-Luisa Brakman,\n904\tAlec Helyar, Alex Beutel, Andrea Vallone, and Saachi\n905\tJain. From hard refusals to safe-completions: To-\n906\tward output-centric safety training.arXiv preprint\n907\tarXiv:2508.09224, 2025.\n908\tYunzhi Zhang, Pieter Abbeel, and Lerrel Pinto. Automatic\n909\tcurriculum learning through value disagreement.Ad-\n910\tvances in Neural Information Processing Systems, 33:\n911\t7648–7659, 2020.\n912\tCaleb Ziems, William Held, Omar Shaikh, Jiaao Chen, Zhe-\n913\thao Zhang, and Diyi Yang. Can large language models\n914\ttransform computational social science?Computational\n915\tLinguistics, 50(1):237–291, 2024.\n916\tAndy Zou, Zifan Wang, Nicholas Carlini, Milad Nasr, J Zico\n917\tKolter, and Matt Fredrikson. Universal and transferable\n918\tadversarial attacks on aligned language models.arXiv\n919\tpreprint arXiv:2307.15043, 2023.\n920\tAndy Zou, Long Phan, Justin Wang, Derek Duenas,\n921\tMaxwell Lin, Maksym Andriushchenko, Rowan Wang,\n922\tZico Kolter, Matt Fredrikson, and Dan Hendrycks. Im-\n923\tproving alignment and robustness with circuit break-\n924\ters, 2024. URL https://arxiv.org/abs/2406.\n925\t04313.\n926\t12\n927\t\n928\tWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n929\t0% 20% 60% 100%\n930\tSafety Pretraining Intervention Timing\n931\t0.60\n932\t0.62\n933\t0.64\n934\t0.66\n935\t0.68\n936\t0.70Separability AUC\n937\tWith Metadata\n938\tWithout Metadata\n939\t0% 20% 60% 100%\n940\tSafety Pretraining Intervention Timing\n941\t0.60\n942\t0.62\n943\t0.64\n944\t0.66\n945\t0.68\n946\t0.70Separability AUC\n947\tWith Metadata\n948\tWithout Metadata\n949\tFigure 7.Separability of safe vs unsafe content (as annotated by GPT-4o-mini) in thefirstlayer of base models (Left) and instruction-tuned\n950\tmodels (Right), as we vary the start timing when we incorporate safety pretraining interventions. The shaded regions denote the standard\n951\tdeviation computed over 5 training runs.\n952\t0% 20% 60% 100%\n953\tSafety Pretraining Intervention Timing\n954\t0.66\n955\t0.67\n956\t0.68\n957\t0.69\n958\t0.70\n959\t0.71Separability AUC\n960\tWith Metadata\n961\tWithout Metadata\n962\t0% 20% 60% 100%\n963\tSafety Pretraining Intervention Timing\n964\t0.675\n965\t0.680\n966\t0.685\n967\t0.690\n968\t0.695\n969\t0.700\n970\t0.705Separability AUC\n971\tWith Metadata\n972\tWithout Metadata\n973\tFigure 8.Separability of safe vs unsafe content (as annotated by GPT-4o-mini) in themiddle (13th) layerof base models (Left) and\n974\tinstruction-tuned models (Right), as we vary the start timing when we incorporate safety pretraining interventions. The shaded regions\n975\tdenote the standard deviation computed over 5 training runs.\n976\tA. Additional Experiments\n977\tAdditional Separability Results.In the main text, we present results on separability of harmful vs safe content in the final\n978\tlayer of the resulting pretraining models. Here, we also present results for the first layer and the middle (13th) layer. We\n979\tobserve similar trends, although we find greater separability in the final layer when compared to earlier layers in the models.\n980\tSafeBeam Overrefusal.Figure 9 extends our overrefusal analysis to the SafeBeam inference setting. Compared to\n981\tstandard top-k sampling, SafeBeam introduces a fifth response category (shortcircuit), which occurs when generation\n982\tterminates upon producing the harmful metadata token. In deployment, such responses can be handled by substituting a\n983\tpredetermined safe completion.\n984\tB. Additional Experimental Details\n985\tSafety EvaluationFor our standard inference evaluations, we use top-k sampling with k= 10 and truncate after 256\n986\ttokens. We average the results over 5 samples. For SafeBeam evaluation, we run a beam search with 10 beams for 256\n987\ttokens, and discard the top 50% of unsafe beams (in terms of probability of the next token being the harmful metadata token).\n988\tWe follow the same exact setting as Maini et al. (2025). We adopt the same GPT-4o-mini judge and judging prompt for\n989\thelpfulness evaluations, and the same HarmBench judge and judge prompt (Mazeika et al., 2024) for our safety evaluations.\n990\t13\n991\t\n992\tWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n993\t0 50 100 150 200 250 300\n994\tCount\n995\t0%\n996\t20%\n997\t60%Pretraining Intervention Timing\n998\tCompliant & Helpful\n999\tCompliant & Unhelpful\n1000\tPartial Refusal\n1001\tFull Refusal\n1002\tShortcircuit\n1003\tFigure 9.Comparison of overrefusal rates on Alpaca when using the SafeBeam inference algorithm. We find thatintroducing pretraining\n1004\tinterventions and metadata earlier during pretraining leads to more helpful compliant behavior, with a slight increase in\n1005\toverrefusal rates.\n1006\tCapabilities EvaluationWe use the default experimental setting for all the datasets as provided as in the LM evaluation\n1007\tharness (Gao et al., 2024). We use the dataset default few-shot settings:0-shotfor ARC-Challenge, OpenBookQA,\n1008\tCommonsenseQA, PIQA, TriviaQA, and WinoGrande (num fewshot=0), and5-shotfor GSM8K ( num fewshot=5;\n1009\tfew-shot examples sampled from the training split).\n1010\tAdversarial JailbreakingFor computing the adversarial suffixes via the GCG algorithm, we learn an adversarial suffix on\n1011\tthe target model, optimizing for the target string of “Sure”. We perform optimization for 500 steps, with an initialization of\n1012\t“x x ... x”, andtop kof 256.\n1013\tFinetuningFor our supervised instruction tuning, we finetune with a batch size of 4 with a learning rate of 2e-5 for one\n1014\tepoch, using cosine learning rate decay with a warmup ratio of 0.03. For our benign finetuning experiments, we perform\n1015\tsupervised finetuning on GSM8k for a single epoch with a learning rate of 2e-5 with the same learning rate schedule as in\n1016\tinstruction tuning.\n1017\tSeparability ExperimentsIn our separability experiments, we use the last token position and the final layer of all models.\n1018\tFor each model, we train a logistic regression classifier on a balanced subset of 500 safe and 500 unsafe examples from the\n1019\ttraining split, and the trained probe is evaluated on the full balanced test set. We report the mean, standard deviation, and\n1020\tstandard error, when computed over five seeds, of the test AUC (area under the ROC curve).\n1021\tC. Additional Discussion\n1022\tWe note that the notion of safety that we focus on in this paper is fairly broad, encompassing general notions of toxicity and\n1023\tharms. This is taken from the taxonomy proposed by the MLCommons (Vidgen et al., 2024), captures a wide variety of\n1024\tpotential harms and undesirable behaviors in different domains. Our method likely requires additional efforts to tackle safety\n1025\tfor specific capabilities, such as bio-weapons and cybersecurity (Li et al., 2024) or reliability of agents in context-dependent\n1026\tscenarios (Andriushchenko et al., 2025; Sam et al., 2025c).\n1027\tWe also note that our results on the separability of safe vs unsafe content has greater implications for the monitoring of\n1028\tsuch models. These experiments contribute to a line of work that develops external monitoring to predict when undesirable\n1029\tgenerations will occur and steer towards safer outputs (Turner et al., 2023; Zou et al., 2024). This may even have implications\n1030\tfor complementary alternative approaches that are adopted in black-box settings and use external models (Sharma et al.,\n1031\t2025; Sam et al., 2025b), which is an area for future study.\n1032\t14\n1033\t\n1034\tWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n1035\tD. Computational Resources\n1036\tFor each variant of the pretraining runs for the 1.7B parameter model on 600B tokens, we used 32 H100 GPUs for roughly\n1037\t6-7 days. Finetuning requires roughly 4 H100 GPUs for 4 hours. Evaluations are run on one L40S GPU.\n1038\t15\n1039\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_012AYThVbkNwud8D2jBMAa8T","session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"68718e4d-7cde-4b70-866e-ed12fd870ecf","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:20:52.843Z"}
