{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XK8LXpHw7GMXaSTjpE5rHj","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t## Header\n2\t\n3\t- **Title:** When Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n4\t- **Authors:** Anonymous (ICML preliminary submission)\n5\t- **Domain tag:** NLP / LLM alignment (safety pretraining curriculum design)\n6\t- **One-line gist:** Empirical study of how the *start time* of safety pretraining interventions (after 0%, 20%, 60%, or 100% of 600B pretraining tokens) affects downstream safety, robustness to benign finetuning, jailbreak robustness, and representational separability of safe vs. harmful content in a 1.7B SmolLM2-style model.\n7\t\n8\t## Core claims\n9\t\n10\t**Methodological / framing contributions**\n11\t- The paper claims to be the first to systematically study *when* during pretraining safety interventions should be introduced, framing intervention timing as a curriculum-learning design choice. Verbatim: \"To our knowledge, we are the first to systematically study this question.\" and \"Our results are the first to establish intervention timing as a key curriculum design choice for safety.\"\n12\t- It introduces a \"safety curriculum\" formalism that varies a single axis — intervention start time — while holding interventions and data sources fixed (interventions adopted unchanged from Maini et al., 2025).\n13\t\n14\t**Empirical contributions**\n15\t- Under standard top-k decoding, \"introducing interventions after a short initial phase of safe-only pretraining (20%-60%) often yields the strongest robustness, with the clearest benefits emerging *after* downstream, benign finetuning.\"\n16\t- Under safety-aware inference (SafeBeam), \"interventions starting from the beginning improve steerability towards safer generations.\"\n17\t- \"Earlier interventions reshape internal representations: linear probes more cleanly separate safe vs harmful examples,\" especially when metadata tagging is included.\n18\t- Delayed interventions (20% or 60%) \"improve robustness to adversarial jailbreaks learned via GCG (Zou et al., 2023), when compared to performing fully safe-only pretraining (100%) and safety interventions applied from the start (0%)\" — but this jailbreak benefit appears only under SafeBeam; under standard inference \"jailbreakability under standard inference does not noticeably change given different intervention timings.\"\n19\t- Capability evaluations show \"no obvious degradations… in fact, earlier pretraining interventions seem to lead to higher levels of capabilities\" (Table 1).\n20\t- Effects are \"not monotonic in the number of intervention tokens,\" so timing matters beyond total quantity of intervention data.\n21\t\n22\t**Artifact contributions**\n23\t- No new datasets or model releases stated. The paper reuses Maini et al. (2025)'s SafeWeb / RefuseWeb / MoralEducation datasets, the SmolLM2 (Allal et al., 2025) pretraining corpus and architecture, and the LitGPT codebase. No release of trained checkpoints is mentioned.\n24\t\n25\t## Methods and experimental setup\n26\t\n27\t**Model and pretraining**\n28\t- 1.7B-parameter SmolLM2 architecture (Allal et al., 2025).\n29\t- Pretraining budget: 600B tokens.\n30\t- Pretraining corpus: FineWeb-Edu, StackOverflow, FineMath, Cosmopedia.\n31\t- Safety-augmented variants: SafeWeb, RefuseWeb, MoralEducation (rephrased / refusal versions of harmful FineWeb-Edu examples from Maini et al., 2025).\n32\t- Pretraining infrastructure: LitGPT with FlashAttention-2 and mixed-precision; \"same hyperparameters (e.g., learning rate schedule, batch size, and sequence length) as in the SmolLM2 pretraining setup\" (specific values not enumerated in this paper).\n33\t- Compute: \"32 H100 GPUs for roughly 6-7 days\" per pretraining run; finetuning ~4 H100 GPUs × 4 hours; evals on one L40S GPU.\n34\t\n35\t**Curriculum settings**\n36\t- Four start times for the same set of interventions: **0% / 20% / 60% / 100%** of the 600B-token budget.\n37\t  - 0% = interventions from the start (mirrors Maini et al., 2025).\n38\t  - 20% / 60% = first an \"all-safe\" phase, then introduce interventions.\n39\t  - 100% = fully safe-only pretraining (mirrors O'Brien et al., 2025).\n40\t- Two intervention bundles studied: (i) all interventions including metadata tagging + SafeBeam, (ii) rephrasing + refusal training only, no metadata.\n41\t\n42\t**Interventions (adopted from Maini et al., 2025)**\n43\t- *Contextualized Rephrasing*: harmful pretraining examples rewritten by a LLaMA3.1 8B model to preserve factual content while framing material as risky.\n44\t- *Refusal Training*: most harmful examples converted into request/refusal conversation pairs and inserted into the pretraining corpus.\n45\t- *Metadata-annotated Pretraining + SafeBeam*: a special token \"<potentially unsafe content>\" is randomly inserted at each token position with **5% probability** in harmful examples; SafeBeam is a beam search modification that drops the top-50% candidate beams whose next-token probability for the harmful metadata token is highest.\n46\t\n47\t**Post-training**\n48\t- Instruction tuning: Ultrachat-200k + AllenAI WildGuardMix + WildJailbreak. Hyperparameters: batch size 4, lr 2e-5, 1 epoch, cosine schedule, warmup 0.03.\n49\t- Benign finetuning: 1 epoch SFT on GSM8K (Cobbe et al., 2021), same hyperparameters as instruction tuning.\n50\t\n51\t**Evaluation pipeline**\n52\tEvaluation occurs at three model stages: base, instruction-tuned, benign-finetuned.\n53\t\n54\t- *Base-model safety*: completion-style harmful-request benchmark from Maini et al. (2025).\n55\t- *Instruction-tuned safety*: HarmBench (Mazeika et al., 2024), TDC (Maloyan et al., 2024), JailbreakBench (Chao et al., 2024), AdvBench (Zou et al., 2023).\n56\t- *Adversarial robustness*: GCG (Zou et al., 2023) with 500 optimization steps, init \"x x … x\", top-k 256, target string \"Sure\".\n57\t- *Benign-finetuned safety*: rerun safety benchmarks after GSM8K finetune.\n58\t- *Capabilities*: ARC-Challenge, CommonsenseQA, GSM8K, OpenBookQA, PIQA, TriviaQA, Winogrande, via the LM Evaluation Harness (Gao et al., 2024). 0-shot for ARC-C, OpenBookQA, CommonsenseQA, PIQA, TriviaQA, WinoGrande; 5-shot for GSM8K.\n59\t- *Helpfulness / overrefusal*: Alpaca (Taori et al., 2023) with GPT-4o-mini judge classifying responses into 4 categories (compliant-helpful, compliant-unhelpful, partial refusal, full refusal); 5th category \"shortcircuit\" added for SafeBeam.\n60\t- *Representation analysis*: logistic-regression linear probe over final-layer last-token activations (also first and 13th layer in appendix), trained on 500 safe + 500 unsafe FineWeb examples labeled by GPT-4o-mini's safety rubric (from Maini et al., 2025); test AUC on a balanced held-out set.\n61\t- Inference settings: top-k sampling with **k=10**, truncated to 256 tokens, averaged over 5 samples; SafeBeam = 10 beams, 256 tokens, dropping the worst 50% beams by harmful-metadata next-token probability.\n62\t\n63\t**Statistical protocol**\n64\t- 5 seeds for top-k inference (shaded standard-deviation regions in Figs. 1, 2, 3, 5).\n65\t- SafeBeam reported as deterministic (\"results are deterministic. When using SafeBeam, the results are deterministic\").\n66\t- Separability AUC reported with mean, std, and std-error over 5 training runs (Sec. B).\n67\t- No formal hypothesis tests, p-values, or confidence intervals are reported; significance claims are presented qualitatively (e.g., \"significantly more robustness\").\n68\t\n69\t**Headline numbers (read off the figures and Table 1)**\n70\t- *Base-model attack success rate vs. timing* (Fig. 1, top-k): U-shape minimum around 20%–60%; rises toward both 0% and 100%; ~maximum near 100% in the 30–35% ASR region; SafeBeam monotonically rises with later timing (lowest ASR at 0%).\n71\t- *Benign-finetuned ASR* (Fig. 2, GSM8K finetune): top-k ASR rises sharply with later intervention start (lowest near 0%–20%, highest at 100% in the 50–60% ASR range); SafeBeam similarly best at 0%.\n72\t- *Instruction-tuned ASR* (Fig. 3): all values within 0–6%; relative ordering qualitatively matches the base-model story.\n73\t- *GCG jailbreak robustness* (Fig. 5): SafeBeam ASR is lowest at 20%/60% (delayed), high at 0% and 100%; top-k roughly flat across timings.\n74\t- *Capabilities* (Table 1, average across 7 benchmarks): 0% = 37.2%, 20% = 36.7%, 60% = 35.6%, 100% = 36.1%. Spread of <2 absolute points.\n75\t- *Separability AUC, final layer* (Fig. 6): 0.785–0.825 range; with-metadata curves trend higher with earlier intervention.\n76\t- *Separability AUC, layer 1 / layer 13* (Figs. 7, 8): 0.60–0.71 range; same qualitative trend, weaker than final-layer.\n77\t\n78\t## Cited claims\n79\t\n80\tThe paper relies on the following non-trivial cited claims; each entry lists the paraphrased/quoted claim, the citation key(s), and the bibliography content for those keys.\n81\t\n82\t- \"alignment effects are often restricted to the first few tokens of a response (Qi et al., 2024b)\" — Qi et al., \"Safety alignment should be made more than just a few tokens deep,\" arXiv:2406.05946, 2024.\n83\t- \"easily circumvented by benign finetuning (Qi et al., 2024a)\" — same Qi et al. preprint cited as 2024a (paper double-cites it as 2024a/2024b).\n84\t- \"adversarial pressure through prompting (Zou et al., 2023; Chao et al., 2023)\" — Zou et al., \"Universal and transferable adversarial attacks on aligned language models,\" arXiv:2307.15043, 2023; Chao et al., \"Jailbreaking black box LLMs in twenty queries,\" arXiv:2310.08419, 2023.\n85\t- \"Misaligned behavior can be further elicited, and even amplified, by malicious or adversarial finetuning on a single task… generalize to other harmful tasks (Betley et al., 2025)\" — Betley et al., \"Emergent misalignment: Narrow finetuning can produce broadly misaligned LLMs,\" arXiv:2502.17424, 2025.\n86\t- \"Recent work has explored removing all harmful content from pretraining data via filtering approaches (O'Brien et al., 2025)\" — O'Brien et al., \"Deep ignorance: Filtering pretraining data builds tamper-resistant safeguards into open-weight LLMs,\" arXiv:2508.06601, 2025.\n87\t- \"Other work, however, has demonstrated that this could lead to a lack of understanding of harmful content, making models more prone to comply with harmful requests (Li et al., 2025)\" — Li, Chen, Viégas, Wattenberg, \"When bad data leads to good models,\" ICML 2025.\n88\t- \"Maini et al. (2025) explored synthetic pretraining interventions… these safety pretraining interventions show promise for improving refusal behavior, robustness to adversarial jailbreaks, and resilience to benign finetuning\" — Maini et al., \"Safety pretraining: Toward the next generation of safe AI,\" arXiv:2504.16980, 2025. **This is the load-bearing prior work; the entire intervention recipe and datasets are inherited from it.**\n89\t- \"Drawing on insights from curriculum learning (Bengio et al., 2009; Graves et al., 2017), which has shown that the ordering of training examples can qualitatively change downstream performance\" — Bengio et al., \"Curriculum learning,\" ICML 2009; Graves et al., \"Automated curriculum learning for neural networks,\" ICML 2017.\n90\t- \"such approaches have led to success in… question-answering (Sachan and Xing, 2016) or reinforcement learning (Zhang et al., 2020)\" — Sachan & Xing, ACL 2016; Zhang, Abbeel, Pinto, NeurIPS 2020.\n91\t- \"Other work has explored when and what types of certain curriculum learning strategies work, demonstrated on small-scale image classification tasks (Wu et al., 2021)\" — Wu, Dyer, Neyshabur, \"When do curricula work?\" ICLR 2021.\n92\t- \"the difficulty in measuring the hardness (Abdin et al., 2024) and similarity of content (Sam et al., 2025a)\" — Abdin et al., \"Phi-3 technical report,\" arXiv:2404.14219, 2024; Sam et al., \"Analyzing similarity metrics for data selection for language model pretraining,\" arXiv:2502.02494, 2025a.\n93\t- \"optimizing source mixtures during pretraining can yield gains in downstream performance and stability (Xie et al., 2023)\" — Xie et al., \"DoReMi: Optimizing data mixtures speeds up language model pretraining,\" NeurIPS 2023.\n94\t- \"adaptive sampling or stage-specific mixtures that emphasize more useful distributions as training evolves (Jiang et al., 2024; Ye et al., 2025)\" — Jiang et al., \"Adaptive data optimization,\" arXiv:2410.11820, 2024; Ye et al., \"Data mixing laws,\" ICLR 2025.\n95\t- \"pretraining in distinct stages can change what models retain and how they transfer (Blakeney et al., 2024)\" — Blakeney et al., \"Does your data spark joy? Performance gains from domain upsampling at the end of training,\" COLM 2024.\n96\t- \"Most language model pretraining employs simple heuristic filters that remove a small amount of harmful content, such as from particular URLs or explicit profanity (Raffel et al., 2020; Xue, 2020)\" — Raffel et al., T5, JMLR 2020; Xue, mT5, arXiv:2010.11934, 2020.\n97\t- \"One early work studied the role of human preferences in language model pretraining (Korbak et al., 2023), finding that it yields lower toxicity scores relative to finetuned models (on the 100M parameter scale)\" — Korbak et al., \"Pretraining language models with human preferences,\" arXiv:2302.08582, 2023.\n98\t- \"heuristic filtering based on educational content (Gunasekar et al., 2023; Penedo et al., 2024), which also correlates with (lower levels of) toxicity. Yet, Vidgen et al. (2024) note that harmful examples remain even in these educational datasets\" — Gunasekar et al., \"Textbooks are all you need,\" arXiv:2306.11644, 2023; Penedo et al., \"The FineWeb datasets,\" arXiv:2406.17557, 2024; Vidgen et al., \"Introducing v0.5 of the AI safety benchmark from MLCommons,\" arXiv:2404.12241, 2024.\n99\t- \"we explore the impacts of filtering unsafe content from the pretraining corpus, training only on safe examples (Li et al., 2025; O'Brien et al., 2025)\" — same Li et al. (2025) ICML and O'Brien et al. (2025) as above.\n100\t- SafeBeam-related: \"leading to safer generations… steer the model towards safer and high-quality completions (Yuan et al., 2025)\" — Yuan et al., \"From hard refusals to safe-completions: Toward output-centric safety training,\" arXiv:2508.09224, 2025.\n101\t- \"the model's efficient learning from high-quality synthetic data (Maini et al., 2024)\" — Maini et al., \"Rephrasing the web,\" ACL 2024.\n102\t- \"external monitoring to predict when undesirable generations will occur and steer towards safer outputs (Turner et al., 2023; Zou et al., 2024)\" — Turner et al., \"Steering language models with activation engineering,\" arXiv:2308.10248, 2023; Zou et al., \"Improving alignment and robustness with circuit breakers,\" arXiv:2406.04313, 2024.\n103\t- \"complementary alternative approaches that are adopted in black-box settings and use external models (Sharma et al., 2025; Sam et al., 2025b)\" — Sharma et al., \"Constitutional classifiers,\" arXiv:2501.18837, 2025; Sam et al., \"Predicting the performance of black-box LLMs through self-queries,\" arXiv:2501.01558, 2025b.\n104\t\n105\t**\"Stated as well-known but uncited\" claims to flag**\n106\t- The intuition that \"interventions introduced too early may degrade capabilities or over-regularize the model before it has learned basic linguistic structure\" is asserted as motivation without citation.\n107\t- The analogy that \"in the human learning process, we often first learn about general knowledge, such as language and arithmetic, before addressing potentially harmful or contro­versial content, such as wars and tragedies\" is invoked as conceptual justification without supporting reference.\n108\t- The claim that \"post-hoc alignment… reshape[s] surface model behavior after completing pretraining\" is framed as background but the supporting citations point to brittleness studies, not a formal demonstration of \"surface-level\" reshaping.\n109\t- \"We attribute this to the model's efficient learning from high-quality syn­thetic data (Maini et al., 2024)\" is a single-citation explanatory claim that may merit additional support (e.g., Gunasekar et al., 2023; the broader synthetic-data line).\n110\t- The Yuan et al. (2025) citation for SafeBeam framing is the only reference for the inference-time safety-completion family; no comparison/distinction is made to Constitutional Classifiers (Sharma et al., 2025), circuit breakers (Zou et al., 2024), or activation steering (Turner et al., 2023) at the methods level.\n111\t\n112\t## Related-work positioning\n113\t\n114\tThe paper structures Related Work into three threads:\n115\t\n116\t1. **Pretraining Safety.** Engages with: heuristic URL/profanity filters (Raffel 2020, Xue 2020); preference-based pretraining (Korbak 2023); educational-content filtering (Gunasekar 2023, Penedo 2024); evidence that harmful content survives (Vidgen 2024); safe-only filtering (Li 2025, O'Brien 2025); synthetic safety interventions (Maini 2025). **Stated differential vs. this thread:** \"We expand upon this work to study the question of when such interventions should be deployed during pretraining\" — the paper frames itself as orthogonal to the *content* of safety interventions and instead studies their *timing*.\n117\t2. **Curriculum Learning.** Engages with: Bengio 2009; Graves 2017; Sachan & Xing 2016 (QA); Zhang 2020 (RL); Wu 2021 (image classification). **Stated differential:** \"Progress in the language model pretraining realm has been relatively static, likely due to the difficulty in measuring the hardness (Abdin et al., 2024) and similarity of content (Sam et al., 2025a), as well as the computational demands.\"\n118\t3. **Stages of Language Model Pretraining.** Engages with: source-mixture optimization (Xie 2023, DoReMi); adaptive data optimization (Jiang 2024); data mixing laws (Ye 2025); domain upsampling at end of training (Blakeney 2024). **Stated differential:** \"Our study is aligned with this perspective but targets a safety-specific question: instead of asking which domains to up-weight, we vary *when* safety-augmented data enters pretraining.\"\n119\t\n120\t**Threads gestured at but not followed through in Related Work**\n121\t- *Post-hoc alignment failure modes* (Qi et al. 2024a/b on shallow alignment, Betley et al. 2025 on emergent misalignment, Zou et al. 2023 / Chao et al. 2023 on jailbreaks) appear in the Introduction's motivation paragraph but are not picked up as a Related Work thread, even though the paper's benign-finetuning evaluation is directly motivated by Qi 2024a.\n122\t- *Inference-time safety steering* (SafeBeam itself, plus the Yuan 2025, Turner 2023, Zou 2024, Sharma 2025 family) is central to the paper's headline result (steerability under SafeBeam) but is discussed only briefly inside §3.1 and §C, not contextualized as related work.\n123\t- *Adversarial-suffix attack literature* beyond GCG (e.g., Chao 2023's PAIR, Andriushchenko 2025's AgentHarm in the references) is used as evaluation tooling without being situated as a body of related work.\n124\t- *Refusal-behavior erosion under benign SFT* (Qi 2024a, Betley 2025) — cited inline, but the paper does not discuss other recent work on this specific phenomenon as a thread.\n125\t- *Capability–safety trade-offs* (e.g., WMDP unlearning, Li 2024) are cited only in Appendix C and not engaged in Related Work.\n126\t\n127\t## Open questions and verification hooks\n128\t\n129\t- **\"Significant\" without statistics.** The paper writes \"introducing pretraining interventions after some initial safe-only pretraining (i.e., at 20% or at 60%) leads to *significantly* more robustness to jailbreaks via GCG when using the SafeBeam inference algorithm\" (§5.4) but reports no significance test, p-values, or confidence intervals. SafeBeam itself is described as deterministic, so the \"significance\" claim against 0%/100% has no obvious variance source disclosed.\n130\t- **Confounded total intervention quantity.** Different start times mean different totals of intervention tokens seen (0% start = most, 60% start = least). The paper acknowledges this (\"certain models have seen more synthetic con­textualized data or refusal data\") and argues effects are non-monotonic, but does not run a controlled experiment that fixes intervention-token count while varying timing.\n131\t- **No matched-token-count baseline.** Only four start times (0/20/60/100) are examined; finer granularity (e.g., 10%, 40%, 80%) and matched-token controls are not reported.\n132\t- **Single model scale.** Only the 1.7B SmolLM2 architecture is studied, on a single 600B-token budget. No scaling-law evidence for whether \"best timing\" generalizes across scales is presented.\n133\t- **Single seed for pretraining (likely).** The 5-seed shaded regions in Figs. 1–3, 5 are explicitly described as \"computed over 5 seeds\" for top-k inference, not 5 pretraining runs. Separability (Fig. 6) reports \"standard deviation computed over 5 training runs,\" implying multiple pretraining runs *only there*. Whether each timing condition's main safety figures are derived from a single pretraining run is ambiguous in the main text. Given a 32×H100 × 6–7 day pretrain cost, this should be verified before making robust claims about timing effects.\n134\t- **Hyperparameter pass-through.** The paper says it uses \"the same hyperparameters (e.g., learning rate schedule, batch size, and sequence length) as in the SmolLM2 pretraining setup\" without reproducing them; the LR schedule across the 0%→intervention boundary is not described (e.g., is the LR schedule continuous, or is intervention introduction aligned with a schedule milestone?).\n135\t- **Definition of \"safe-only\" data.** The pre-intervention phase trains on FineWeb-Edu / StackOverflow / FineMath / Cosmopedia, but Vidgen et al. (2024) — cited by the paper — show harmful content remains in educational datasets. The paper uses \"safe-only\" as a label without explicit filtering verification of the pre-intervention corpus.\n136\t- **Judge dependency.** Both safety classification (HarmBench judge) and helpfulness classification (GPT-4o-mini) and the safety rubric used for separability labels (GPT-4o-mini, Maini et al.'s rubric) rely on closed-model judges. No human inter-rater agreement or judge robustness analysis is reported.\n137\t- **Capability comparison missing a no-intervention baseline.** Table 1 reports 0%/20%/60%/100% but no \"no safety pretraining at all\" run (i.e., the same SmolLM2 trained on its original mixture without safety modifications), so absolute capability cost is not measurable from this table alone.\n138\t- **Self-citation density.** Multiple references to Sam et al. (2025a/b/c) are present — these are framed as supporting citations; relevance and orthogonality to the paper's contributions could be examined.\n139\t- **GCG protocol asymmetry.** GCG suffixes are optimized \"on each model\" with target string \"Sure\" — comparison fairness across the four timings depends on whether the optimization budget (500 steps, top-k 256) achieves similar attack success on identically prompted base models, which is not reported.\n140\t- **SafeBeam result discussed for the base model but the inference algorithm depends on metadata tokens.** The paper does not separately ablate the contribution of metadata tagging vs. the SafeBeam beam-pruning rule; both are bundled in the \"with metadata\" condition.\n141\t- **Helpfulness \"shortcircuit\" handling.** Figure 4 (top-k) excludes a 5th \"shortcircuit\" category that exists for SafeBeam (Fig. 9). When comparing absolute compliance rates between top-k and SafeBeam, the categorical schemas differ — a verification hook for any side-by-side overrefusal claim.\n142\t- **Apparent typo / inconsistency in text.** §5.5: \"introducing interventions from the start yields the highest linear-probe AUC\" while Fig. 6 axis values (0.785–0.825 with metadata) and shaded SDs may overlap — the qualitative monotonic claim should be checked against the numeric error bars.\n143\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_017REXY1vT1smKycyLMCZ23D","session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"e2d07c0f-7362-4680-810c-a8677143d16d","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:26:17.524Z"}
