{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014hNTLMzXWLJANfbPL25Fni","type":"tool_result","content":"800\tarXiv:2508.06601, 2025.\n801\tLong Ouyang, Jeffrey Wu, Xu Jiang, Diogo Almeida, Car-\n802\troll Wainwright, Pamela Mishkin, Chong Zhang, Sand-\n803\thini Agarwal, Katarina Slama, Alex Ray, et al. Training\n804\tlanguage models to follow instructions with human feed-\n805\tback.Advances in neural information processing systems,\n806\t35:27730–27744, 2022.\n807\tGuilherme Penedo, Hynek Kydl ´ıˇcek, Loubna Ben allal,\n808\tAnton Lozhkov, Margaret Mitchell, Colin Raffel, Lean-\n809\tdro V on Werra, and Thomas Wolf. The fineweb datasets:\n810\tDecanting the web for the finest text data at scale, 2024.\n811\tURLhttps://arxiv.org/abs/2406.17557.\n812\tXiangyu Qi, Ashwinee Panda, Kaifeng Lyu, Xiao Ma,\n813\tSubhrajit Roy, Ahmad Beirami, Prateek Mittal, and Peter\n814\tHenderson. Safety alignment should be made more than\n815\tjust a few tokens deep.arXiv preprint arXiv:2406.05946,\n816\t2024a.\n817\tXiangyu Qi, Ashwinee Panda, Kaifeng Lyu, Xiao Ma,\n818\tSubhrajit Roy, Ahmad Beirami, Prateek Mittal, and Pe-\n819\tter Henderson. Safety alignment should be made more\n820\tthan just a few tokens deep, 2024b. URL https:\n821\t//arxiv.org/abs/2406.05946.\n822\tRafael Rafailov, Archit Sharma, Eric Mitchell, Christo-\n823\tpher D Manning, Stefano Ermon, and Chelsea Finn. Di-\n824\trect preference optimization: Your language model is\n825\tsecretly a reward model.Advances in Neural Information\n826\tProcessing Systems, 36:53728–53741, 2023.\n827\tColin Raffel, Noam Shazeer, Adam Roberts, Katherine Lee,\n828\tSharan Narang, Michael Matena, Yanqi Zhou, Wei Li,\n829\tand Peter J Liu. Exploring the limits of transfer learning\n830\twith a unified text-to-text transformer.Journal of machine\n831\tlearning research, 21(140):1–67, 2020.\n832\tAlexander Robey, Zachary Ravichandran, Vijay Kumar,\n833\tHamed Hassani, and George J Pappas. Jailbreaking\n834\tllm-controlled robots.arXiv preprint arXiv:2410.13691,\n835\t2024.\n836\tMrinmaya Sachan and Eric Xing. Easy questions first? a\n837\tcase study on curriculum learning for question answering.\n838\tInProceedings of the 54th Annual Meeting of the Asso-\n839\tciation for Computational Linguistics (V olume 1: Long"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_017REXY1vT1smKycyLMCZ23D","session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"960af279-ce8b-473f-8217-066cb8a64b0a","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:26:24.480Z"}
