{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DAnNFHZRJknGqaM4tENrAD","type":"tool_result","content":"375\tevaluation setting that incorporates adversarial jailbreaking,\n376\twhere we learn adversarial suffixes via the GCG algorithm\n377\t(Zou et al., 2023) that are optimized on each model to in-\n378\tcrease the rate of compliance with harmful requests.\n379\tFinally, we evaluate the models after an epoch of benign,\n380\tsupervised finetuning on a helpful, non-adversarial dataset\n381\tof GSM8K (Cobbe et al., 2021), which is common practice\n382\tfor mathematical reasoning, without any focus on safety or\n383\talignment. Despite this being non-adversarial data, other\n384\tworks have demonstrated that such rounds of supervised\n385\tfinetuning can erode aligned behaviors (Qi et al., 2024a;\n386\tBetley et al., 2025).\n387\t4.2. Capability and Helpfulness Evaluations\n388\tWhen introducing safety interventions that may increase\n389\trefusal rates, it is crucial to assess any impact on model\n390\tcapabilities and helpfulness. For capabilities, we evaluate\n391\ton a suite of standard benchmarks spanning general knowl-\n392\tedge (ARC-Challenge, TriviaQA), commonsense reasoning\n393\t(CommonsenseQA, OpenBookQA, PIQA, Winogrande),\n394\tand mathematical reasoning (GSM8K). Additional experi-\n395\tment details are deferred to Appendix B.\n396\t5\n397\t\n398\tWhen Should We Introduce Safety Interventions During Pretraining?\n399\t0 50 100 150 200 250 300\n400\tCount\n401\t0%\n402\t20%\n403\t60%\n404\t100%Pretraining Intervention Timing\n405\tCompliant & Helpful\n406\tCompliant & Unhelpful\n407\tPartial Refusal Full Refusal\n408\tFigure 4.Comparison of overrefusal rates on Alpaca (Taori et al., 2023) when using standard (Top-k) sampling for inference. We find that\n409\tincorporating interventions earlier during pretraining leads to a better compliance rate on benign requests.\n410\tTo measure helpfulness, we evaluate model compliance\n411\ton benign requests from the Alpaca dataset (Taori et al.,\n412\t2023). We use GPT-4o-mini as a judge to classify each\n413\tresponse into one of four categories: (1) compliant and\n414\thelpful, (2) compliant but unhelpful, (3) partial refusal, or"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_017REXY1vT1smKycyLMCZ23D","session_id":"fe1f808f-01ab-4006-ad95-1fe7fc2eca89","uuid":"a073d1e0-ddf4-43c6-aa67-6af7fb07ce0f","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:26:40.529Z"}
