{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_015DnAmoCJQT5EnYEDtrWNCt","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_012BWpww6hxu8oGW4VqL6HYH","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"Run extractor on Private PoEtry paper","subagent_type":"extractor","prompt":"You are the `extractor` sub-agent of the `quadrant` ICML reviewer. Read your role definition at `/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/.claude/agents/extractor.md` if needed for protocol details, then produce a digest for the paper.\n\nPAPER TO EXTRACT\n- Title: \"Private PoEtry: Private In-Context Learning via Product of Experts\"\n- Paper ID: 5a88f942-4cd4-4ac3-b8fc-c5b20fa7d739\n- Domain tags from platform: Trustworthy-ML, NLP\n- Cleaned full text is at `/tmp/quadrant_paper_5a88f942/paper_clean.txt` (~81k chars, 20 pages). Read it.\n- Original PDF text (with stray line numbers) is at `/tmp/quadrant_paper_5a88f942/paper.txt` if you need to disambiguate any cleaned section.\n\nABSTRACT (for grounding):\n\"In-context learning (ICL) enables Large Language Models (LLMs) to adapt to new tasks with only a small set of examples at inference time, thereby avoiding task-specific fine-tuning. However, in-context examples may contain privacy-sensitive information that should not be revealed through model outputs. Existing differential privacy (DP) approaches to ICL are either computationally expensive or rely on heuristics with limited effectiveness, including context oversampling, synthetic data generation, or unnecessary thresholding. We reformulate private ICL through the lens of a Product-of-Experts model. This gives a theoretically grounded framework, and the algorithm can be trivially parallelized. We evaluate our method across five datasets in text classification, math, and vision-language. We find that our method improves accuracy by more than 30 percentage points on average compared to prior DP-ICL methods, while maintaining strong privacy guarantees.\"\n\nOUTPUT\n- Markdown digest with the six required sections (Header / Core claims / Methods and experimental setup / Cited claims / Related-work positioning / Open questions and verification hooks).\n- Be exact with numbers, table/figure references, baseline names, dataset names, ε values, etc.\n- Do not score or judge — that is for the four lens sub-agents.\n- Write the final digest to `/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/reasoning/5a88f942_extractor.md` and ALSO return it as your final message."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1239,"cache_read_input_tokens":84676,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1239},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"61b992b7-c7e9-4fd1-9cce-d1e8223d902f","uuid":"f40c66cb-7025-4e9c-882c-56d681b6a563"}
