{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013FYWPTXdQPPTroDVpKuG2c","type":"tool_result","content":"1\tPrivate PoEtry: Private In-Context Learning via Product of Experts\n2\tAnonymous Authors1\n3\tAbstract\n4\tIn-context learning (ICL) enables Large Language\n5\tModels (LLMs) to adapt to new tasks with only a\n6\tsmall set of examples at inference time, thereby\n7\tavoiding task-specific fine-tuning. However, in-\n8\tcontext examples may contain privacy-sensitive\n9\tinformation that should not be revealed through\n10\tmodel outputs. Existing differential privacy (DP)\n11\tapproaches to ICL are either computationally ex-\n12\tpensive or rely on heuristics with limited effec-\n13\ttiveness, including context oversampling, syn-\n14\tthetic data generation, or unnecessary threshold-\n15\ting. We reformulate private ICL through the\n16\tlens of a Product-of-Experts model. This gives a\n17\ttheoretically grounded framework, and the algo-\n18\trithm can be trivially parallelized. We evaluate\n19\tour method across five datasets in text classifi-\n20\tcation, math, and vision-language. We find that\n21\tour method improves accuracy by more than 30\n22\tpercentage points on average compared to prior\n23\tDP-ICL methods, while maintaining strong pri-\n24\tvacy guarantees.\n25\t1. Introduction\n26\tThe advancement of large language models (LLMs) has\n27\tcreated an insatiable appetite for training data. Much of\n28\tthe world’s most valuable data, however, remains siloed in\n29\tprivate repositories: from healthcare records and financial\n30\ttransactions to personal communications and proprietary\n31\tbusiness documents. While such data would be highly in-\n32\tformative for downstream learning, directly incorporating it\n33\tinto model training raises fundamental privacy concerns.\n34\tStandard approaches to privacy-preserving learning rely on\n35\tdifferential privacy (DP) applied to gradient-based optimiza-\n36\ttion. In the context of large pretrained models, however, DP\n37\ttraining is often impractical: it requires careful tuning of\n38\tbatch sizes and gradient clipping, introduces substantial opti-\n39\t1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\n40\tAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n41\t<anon.email@domain.com>.\n42\tPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\n43\ton Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\n44\tmization noise, and typically leads to significant degradation\n45\tin utility, especially in low-data or highly heterogeneous set-\n46\ttings (Kurakin et al., 2022; Raisa et al., 2024). These chal-\n47\tlenges make fine-tuning large models under strong privacy\n48\tconstraints costly and brittle in practice.\n49\tIn-context learning (ICL) offers an alternative paradigm that\n50\tavoids gradient-based updates altogether. By conditioning\n51\ta frozen LLM on a small set of task-relevant examples\n52\tprovided at inference time, ICL enables adaptation to local\n53\tdata without modifying model parameters or performing\n54\tprivacy-sensitive optimization.\n55\tThis approach has been demonstrated to be effective in text\n56\tclassification, translation (Brown et al., 2020), mathemati-\n57\tcal reasoning (Agarwal et al., 2024), and vision-language\n58\ttasks (Tsimpoukelli et al., 2021). However, recent work\n59\tshows that in-context learning can leak privacy about the\n60\tinput (Duan et al., 2023b; Choi et al.; Wang et al., 2023).\n61\tThis is a serious problem for Agentic AI settings, such\n62\tas Retrieval-Augmented-Generation (Lewis et al., 2020) or\n63\t“tool calling” (Fan et al., 2025), where agents are expected to\n64\tutilize small amounts of data with varying privacy settings.\n65\tWe give examples of this setting with important privacy\n66\tconstraints in Section 1.1.\n67\tThe current approaches for differentially private ICL either\n68\tintroduce unnecessary bottlenecks or limit themselves to\n69\tineffective data structures. For example, Tang et al. (2024)\n70\tuses an LLM to generate synthetic data as a private bottle-\n71\tneck, to then re-input the synthetic data into the context of\n72\tthe LLM to create a response. Other prior work suggests\n73\tPrivacy-Amplification-by-Subsampling (PbS) by calling the\n74\tLLM hundreds of times or by directly comparing thresh-\n75\tolded logits from an ICL-LLM, thereby discarding key infor-\n76\tmation contained in the logits (Wu et al., 2024). Moreover,\n77\tthese methods have been evaluated primarily on simple text\n78\tclassification datasets, with limited validation on more chal-\n79\tlenging tasks, such as mathematical problem-solving and\n80\tvision-language tasks common in ICL applications.\n81\tWe introduce an approach for differentially private ICL\n82\tbased on the Product-of-Experts (PoE) model (Hinton, 2002;\n83\tHeskes, 1997). Originally proposed as a probabilistic en-\n84\tsemble method, PoE models combine multiple distributions\n85\t(“experts”) by multiplying their probabilities and renormal-\n86\tizing, thereby emphasizing agreement among experts while\n87\t\n88\t--- PAGE BREAK ---\n89\t\n90\tPrivate PoEtry: Private In-Context Learning via Product of Experts\n91\tsharply down-weighting inconsistent predictions. Our key\n92\tinsight is that sampling from an LLM conditioned on mul-\n93\ttiple in-context examples can be naturally approximated\n94\tby a Product-of-Experts formulation, where each example\n95\tinduces a local expert over the outputs. This approxima-\n96\ttion reveals a way to use the model’s predictive scores (soft\n97\tscores), rather than the thresholded hard votes used in pre-\n98\tvious work (Wu et al., 2024). Experimental results across\n99\tfive datasets show that this new viewpoint yields consis-\n100\ttent improvements over earlier methods. We provide both\n101\ta theoretical motivation for the underlying conditional in-\n102\tdependence assumption and complement the experimental\n103\tresults with an empirical privacy attack. In summary, the\n104\tcontributions of this paper are threefold:\n105\tPoE Formulation of private ICLWe reformulate ICL with\n106\ta Product-of-Experts model. This decomposition naturally\n107\tenables per-example privacy analysis while maintaining the\n108\tnuance in the “soft” predictive probabilities.\n109\tEfficient and Accurate Private Inference.Our method\n110\tis computationally efficient, trivially parallelizable, and\n111\tachieves substantially higher accuracy than prior private\n112\tICL approaches across five benchmarks spanning text, math-\n113\tematics, and vision-language tasks.\n114\tEmpirical Privacy Evaluation.We complement the theo-\n115\tretical analysis with a membership inference attack, demon-\n116\tstrating improved empirical privacy on four datasets.\n117\t1.1. Background and Threat Model\n118\tIn-context learning (ICL) operates by providing an LLM\n119\twith a prompt that includes both the user’s query and a col-\n120\tlection of context examples. The model conditions its output\n121\tdistribution on this complete textual input, enabling task-\n122\tspecific behavior through in-context adaptation rather than\n123\tparameter fine-tuning. While this mechanism enables flexi-\n124\tble and efficient adaptation, it creates a privacy vulnerability:\n125\tthe model’s responses may inadvertently reveal information\n126\tabout the sensitive context examples in the prompt.\n127\tIn-context learning is mainly used for small datasets (five\n128\tto fifty samples) (Brown et al., 2020; Agarwal et al., 2024;\n129\tTsimpoukelli et al., 2021), and the LLM has local access\n130\tto these private samples. After “learning” on these private\n131\tsamples, the LLM outputs should not reveal any private\n132\tcontextual information. However, several publications high-\n133\tlighted that appropriately prompted queries can reveal in-\n134\tformation about the context (Duan et al., 2023b; Choi et al.;\n135\tWang et al., 2023). This is the threat model that we study\n136\tin this paper, and it is particularly relevant to Agentic AI.\n137\tWith Retrieval-Augmented-Generation (RAG), AI agents\n138\tcan be employed to use local data (Lewis et al., 2020) – also\n139\tnamed “tool-calling” (Fan et al., 2025). Such a call to RAG\n140\tcould leak private information. Several use cases of tool-use\n141\tregarding the local data require privacy protection:\n142\t• An LLM accesses all emails in an inbox and is asked\n143\tto respond to a new email, but the private details in the\n144\tuser’s emails should not be leaked.\n145\t• An LLM sees customer interactions and helps a new cus-\n146\ttomer, but other customers’ details should not be leaked.\n147\t• A robot equipped with a Vision-Language Model (VLM)\n148\tcleans several houses and learns to improve cleaning in\n149\tthe next house, but the private layout of each house should\n150\tnot be leaked.\n151\t• A financial LLM sees financial reports of several clients\n152\tand writes a financial report for a new client, but the\n153\tprivate bank details should not be leaked.\n154\tIn all such settings, the LLM can learn from examples in\n155\tcontext, thereby increasing its accuracy. However, in each\n156\ttask, there could be a severe privacy loss if the LLM’s\n157\toutput, directly or indirectly, reveals an individual’s details.\n158\tFigure 1 gives an overview of our research setting.\n159\t2. Related Work\n160\tSeveral recent works have addressed differentially private\n161\tin-context learning, though they rely on computationally\n162\texpensive intermediate steps. Tang et al. (2024) identified\n163\tsynthetic data generation as a privacy bottleneck, where the\n164\tfinal answer is sampled from the synthetic context. This ap-\n165\tproach requires generating synthetic tokens autoregressively\n166\tfrom a sampled subset of the full dataset, which is a com-\n167\tputationally costly step. Moreover, the question-dependent\n168\ttoken generation limits its applicability as a general-purpose\n169\talgorithm. Other work (Sun et al., 2025) also explores\n170\tthe use of synthetic data as a privacy mechanism. In con-\n171\ttrast, Wu et al. (2024) employs Privacy-Amplification-by-\n172\tSubsampling (Balle et al., 2018), but experimental evalua-\n173\ttion in Section 4 shows that this yields suboptimal accuracy.\n174\tBeyond in-context learning, several works explored differ-\n175\tentially private prompt tuning for personalization. Hong\n176\tet al. (2024) focused on remote prompt learning, enabling\n177\tsoft-prompt optimization for a dataset on a remote server\n178\twithout local computation; Duan et al. (2023a) addressed\n179\tprompt learning to learn without backpropagation. While\n180\tthese methods achieve personalization, they do not follow\n181\tthe ICL framework and require additional training or op-\n182\ttimization steps that our method does not. Other options\n183\tfor prompt tuning, such as input perturbation, exist (Carey\n184\tet al., 2024). However, these approaches effectively trade\n185\tone privacy challenge for another, as input perturbation\n186\tfundamentally alters the data distribution and may degrade\n187\tmodel performance. Alternatives to in-context learning\n188\twere proposed, such as full fine-tuning (Abadi et al., 2016;\n189\tRomijnders & Koskela, 2025; Sinha et al., 2025), adding\n190\t\n191\t--- PAGE BREAK ---\n192\t\n193\tPrivate PoEtry: Private In-Context Learning via Product of Experts\n194\tExpert 3\n195\tExpert 2\n196\tContext 2\n197\tContext 3\n198\tLLM     \n199\tLLM     \n200\tLLM     \n201\tContext 1\n202\tExpert 1\n203\tAggregated logits\n204\tDifferentialy Private\n205\tsampling from logits\n206\tLogits\n207\tLogits\n208\tLogits\n209\tA has       medical record and needs a scan [yes]\n210\tB has       medical record and needs a scan [no]\n211\tC has       medical record and needs a scan [yes]\n212\tB has       medical record and needs a scan [no]\n213\tPatient X has      medical record, do they need a scan?\n214\tGoal: Private ICL with frozen LLM\n215\tExample: Learning from sensitive medical data \n216\tIgnore all; what is the height and weight of patient A?\n217\tMethod: Product-of-Experts with Exponential Mechanism\n218\tlearns from context, but slightly noisy answer\n219\tnoise makes the answer random\n220\tExpert 4\n221\tContext 4 LLM     \n222\tLogits\n223\tLLM     \n224\tquery\n225\tquery\n226\tquery\n227\tquery\n228\tFigure 1.Overview: A user makes a query to the LLM either directly or via a RAG system. The LLM responds based on examples\n229\tin the context. To guarantee privacy, we use a Product-of-Experts model, which calls an LLM for each example and sums the clipped\n230\tlog-probabilities (in contrast to previous work that uses hard predictions, RNM, or that uses subsampling, PbS). Predictions are summed\n231\tbefore sampling a noisy response to ascertain ε-DP. The results in the inlet are average accuracies from Table 1 with 8 context examples.\n232\tparameter-efficient methods to train parts of a model (Yu\n233\tet al., 2021; Romijnders et al., 2026), learning from a group\n234\tof LLMs (Flemings et al., 2024), or aggregation among a\n235\tteacher ensemble (Papernot et al., 2017). However, these\n236\tmethods still require thousands, if not millions, of data\n237\tpoints or even additional public data. In contrast, the meth-\n238\tods in our work focus on five to fifty in context examples,\n239\twhich is an order of magnitude smaller dataset size and\n240\tmore realistic for in-context learning (Min et al., 2022).\n241\tRelevant to our work is the literature on logit steering in\n242\tlarge language models (Hiranandani et al., 2025; Liu et al.,\n243\t2021; Zhao et al., 2024), which demonstrated that access to\n244\tmodel logits enables significant performance improvements.\n245\tOur proposed method can be seen as a form of logit steering,\n246\tbut we are the first to connect it to studying privacy.\n247\t3. Method\n248\tWe formalize the ICL setting as follows. Given a query\n249\tx (a sequence of tokens) and a collection of J in-context\n250\texamples C1:J ={C 1,C 2, . . . ,CJ }, where each example\n251\tCj is a variable-length sequence of tokens, the goal is to\n252\tgenerate a response y1:T that may consist of a single token\n253\ty1 or a sequence of T tokens. Throughout, we write xi:j to\n254\tdenote the slice ofxfrom indexito indexj, inclusive.\n255\tThe sample from an LLM in ICL can be viewed as a sam-\n256\tple from a conditional probability distribution. The model\n257\tgenerates the response by sampling from the distribution\n258\tover possible outputs, conditioned on both the query and\n259\tthe in-context examples. This distribution takes the form:\n260\tp(y1:T |x,C 1:J)(1)\n261\tHowever, directly analyzing this distribution from a dif-\n262\tferential privacy perspective is challenging, as one cannot\n263\ttrace the influence of individual examples Cj on the final\n264\toutput. To derive the privacy mechanism, we first write\n265\tthe autoregressive generation process. In auto-regressive\n266\tlanguage generation, the full sequence probability overy1:T\n267\tcan be written as a product of conditional probabilities over\n268\tindividual tokens given the previously generated tokens.\n269\tp(y1:T |x,C1:J) =p(y 1|x,C 1:J)p(y2|y1,x,C 1:J),· · ·,\n270\tp(yt|y<t,x,C 1:J),· · ·, p(y T |y<T ,x,C 1:J)\n271\tCrucially, p(yt|y<t,x,C 1:J) is the conditional distribution\n272\tfor sampling the next token based on previous tokens, query,\n273\tand context. To obtain a distribution amenable to privacy\n274\tanalysis, we introduce the Product-of-Experts (PoE) model\n275\tas an approximate distribution. This model is a form of\n276\tensembling multiple experts and was introduced in the pi-\n277\toneering work by Heskes (1997) on “logarithmic opinion\n278\tpools” and the subsequent formalization as “Product-of-\n279\tExperts” by Hinton (2002). For a token yt in the sequence,\n280\twe introduce the Product-of-Experts (PoE) approximation,\n281\twhere each expert depends on a single context example:\n282\tp(yt|y<t,x,C 1:J)≈ 1\n283\tZ\n284\tY\n285\tj\n286\tp(yt|y<t,x,C j)(2)\n287\tThe Product-of-Experts model approximates the distribu-\n288\ttion conditioned on all context examples, C1:J, as the prod-\n289\tuct of J predictions, one for each context example alone,\n290\tp(yt|y<t,x,C j). Z is the normalization constant. This\n291\tproduct structure enables privacy analysis by allowing one\n292\t\n293\t--- PAGE BREAK ---\n294\t\n295\tPrivate PoEtry: Private In-Context Learning via Product of Experts\n296\tto bound the contribution of each example to the final out-\n297\tput separately. The model implicitly makes a conditional\n298\tindependence assumption, as does earlier work (Wu et al.,\n299\t2024). This assumption will be explained in Section 3.2.\n300\t3.1. Differential Privacy from the Product-of-Experts\n301\tFrom the PoE model, a computational structure arises that\n302\tis amenable to privacy analysis. The product in Equation 2\n303\tcan be seen as a summation in logarithmic units:\n304\tlog\n305\tJY\n306\tj=1\n307\tp(yt|y<t,x,C j) =\n308\tJX\n309\tj=1\n310\tlogp(y t|y<t,x,C j)(3)\n311\tSuch a summation can be viewed as a sum of utilities, which\n312\twe clip and use the exponential mechanism from Dwork &\n313\tRoth (2014). Privacy is defined as the difference between\n314\ttwo context sets, where one context example can differ, con-\n315\tstituting the privacy unit (Chua et al., 2024a). The algorithm\n316\tis outlined in Algorithm 1. Importantly, the clipping is ap-\n317\tplied in Line 7, and the exponential mechanism in Line 9.\n318\tWe will make experimental comparisons in the next section.\n319\tThe clipping-operator clipγ(l) passes values li ∈[−γ,0]\n320\tunchanged and sets all other values to zero. We give a proof\n321\tsketch for differential privacy here.\n322\tTheorem 3.1(Differential Privacy of PoEtry algorithm).\n323\tAlgorithm 1 satisfies (ε, δ)-differential privacy with respect\n324\tto adjacent context sets that differ by at most one in-context\n325\texample. The noise parameter σ is set for a given privacy\n326\tbudget(ε, δ)and clipping boundγ.\n327\tProof. Each utility value is clipped to the rangeli ∈[−γ,0] .\n328\tTherefore, sampling the class for a single token proportional\n329\tto exp[ ˆyiε/(2γ)] satisfies DP (Dwork & Roth, 2014). The\n330\tcomposition theorem is due to Kairouz et al. (2015). A\n331\tdetailed proof is given in Appendix B.1.\n332\t3.2. Theoretical Analysis\n333\tIn addition to the experimental comparison, we provide a\n334\ttheoretical perspective on our Product of Experts view. We\n335\tfocus on the conditional independence assumption in our\n336\tand previous work and show that it is less restrictive than\n337\tit may appear once we examine how contexts are actually\n338\tused. In the examples (see Section 1.1), the agent does\n339\tnot see the entire private in-context set of examples at once\n340\t(e.g., the whole inbox, the full code base, or the full image\n341\tstream). Instead, it is exposed to a disjoint, often singular\n342\tsubset of context when answering a query: a few emails\n343\tabout the current topic, a few recent code diffs, or a few\n344\timage-label pairs for a VLM evaluation. It is natural to\n345\tmodel this selection step as drawing i.i.d. “views” from a\n346\tmuch larger underlying private state: for instance, sampling\n347\tAlgorithm 1In-context learning with differential privacy\n348\tfrom a Product-of-Experts approximation to LLMs.\n349\tRequire:x , query; C1,C 2,· · ·,C J, in-context exam-\n350\tples; Tmax, number of tokens; LM(·|·), pretrained and\n351\tfrozen LLM that returns log-probabilities; (ε, δ), DP\n352\tparameters;γ, clipping-bound.\n353\tEnsure:z: differentially private response\n354\t1:z←[]{Initialize empty response}\n355\t2:Use binary search to find smallestσs.t.\n356\tε≤T σ(e σ −1) +σ\n357\tp\n358\t2Tlogδ −1\n359\t3:fort= 1toT max do\n360\t4: ˆy←0{Initialize with zeros}\n361\t5:forj= 1toJdo\n362\t6:l←LM(·|z,x,C j)\n363\t7: ˆy← ˆy+clip γ(l)\n364\t8:end for\n365\t9:y←Sampleiproportional toexp[ ˆyiσ/(2γ)]\n366\t10:z←z+ [y]{Append token to response}\n367\t11:end for\n368\t12:returnz\n369\ta few emails from the distribution of inbox messages, or\n370\tsampling a few crops or patches from a full image.\n371\tFormally, we model a high-dimensional latent state S (the\n372\tfull inbox, repository, or dataset), and each in-context ex-\n373\tample Cj is obtained by applying a randomized projection\n374\toperator Pj to S (e.g., a random retrieval rule, a random\n375\tcrop, or a random subsequence). Different choices of Pj\n376\tgive different examples, and it is reasonable to treat these\n377\tviews as independent conditional on S. Under this “many\n378\tsmall views of a large object” model, each example is an\n379\tindependent low-dimensional summary of the same under-\n380\tlying state. The theorem below shows that, aggregating the\n381\tinfluence of a number of such independent views, the result-\n382\ting probability distribution converges to the distribution that\n383\twe would have obtained if we could condition directly on\n384\tthe high-dimensional stateS.\n385\tWe now state the assumptions for the theorem. The key\n386\tis that, while transformer attention creates cross-example\n387\tinteractions, we assume these interactions remain bounded\n388\tas the number of examples grows, whereas the contribution\n389\tfrom individual examples accumulates.\n390\tAssumption 3.2. Bounded interactionFor a given query\n391\tx and output token y, we decompose the unnormalized\n392\tLLM log-probability distribution as follows:\n393\tlog ˜pLLM(y|x,C 1:J) =\n394\tJX\n395\tj=1\n396\tψ(y,C j;x) +R J(y,C 1:J),\n397\twhere ψ(y,C j;x) is the log-likelihood contribution of ex-\n398\tample Cj, satisfying |ψ(y,C;x)| ≤M for some M <∞ ;\n399\t\n400\t--- PAGE BREAK ---"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_012BWpww6hxu8oGW4VqL6HYH","session_id":"61b992b7-c7e9-4fd1-9cce-d1e8223d902f","uuid":"63f0de76-61cc-4983-b5b6-1e0443d0e33b","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:40:20.868Z"}
