{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HKw8ArB9Cyc9QvJmVuaggk","type":"tool_result","content":"400\t--- PAGE BREAK ---\n401\t\n402\tPrivate PoEtry: Private In-Context Learning via Product of Experts\n403\tRJ(y,C 1:J) is a residual capturing cross-example interac-\n404\ttions, satisfying |RJ(y,C 1:J)| ≤B uniformly in J, y, and\n405\tthe choice of examples, for someB <∞.\n406\tRemark3.3 (Interpretation of Assumption).The assumption\n407\tstates that cross-example attention effects, in which the rep-\n408\tresentation of Ci is modified by attending to Cj, contribute\n409\ta bounded amount to the final logits. This is plausible when:\n410\t1) Each example primarily attends to the query x and to\n411\titself, with limited cross-example attention; 2) The model’s\n412\tin-context learning mechanism operates via a “soft retrieval”\n413\twhere each example independently predicts an output; 3)\n414\tAttention weights to other examples are O(1/J) , so their\n415\ttotal contribution remains bounded.\n416\tTheorem 3.4(Convergence to Full-Context Distribution\n417\tunder Bounded Interaction).Let S be a private state, and let\n418\tC1,C 2, . . .\n419\ti.i.d.\n420\t∼P(C|S) be independent views. Suppose\n421\tAssumption 3.2 holds with constants M and B. Define the\n422\tnormalized LLM probability distribution:\n423\tpJ(y|x,C 1:J) := ˜pLLM(y|x,C 1:J)P\n424\ty′ ˜pLLM(y′ |x,C 1:J) .(4)\n425\tDefine the limiting distribution:\n426\tp⋆(y|x,S) := pLLM(y|x) exp\n427\t\u0000 ¯ψ(y,S;x)\n428\t\u0001\n429\tP\n430\ty′ pLLM(y′ |x) exp\n431\t\u0000 ¯ψ(y ′,S;x)\n432\t\u0001 ,\n433\t(5)\n434\twhere ¯ψ(y,S;x) :=E C∼P(·|S) [ψ(y,C;x)] is the ex-\n435\tpected marginal contribution. Then for almost everyS:\n436\t\n437\t\n438\tpJ(· |x,C 1:J)−p ⋆(· |x,S)\n439\t\n440\t\n441\ta.s.\n442\t− − →0asJ→ ∞.\n443\t(6)\n444\tProof. Define the score vector uJ(y) := 1\n445\tJ log ˜pLLM(y|\n446\tx,C 1:J). By Assumption 3.2:\n447\tuJ(y) = 1\n448\tJ\n449\tJX\n450\tj=1\n451\tψ(y,C j;x) + 1\n452\tJ RJ(y,C 1:J).(7)\n453\tWe analyze each term.Sum term:By the strong\n454\tlaw of large numbers (SLLN), Cj\n455\ti.i.d.\n456\t∼P(· |S)\n457\tand |ψ(y,C j;x)| ≤M : 1\n458\tJ\n459\tPJ\n460\tj=1 ψ(y,C j;x)\n461\ta.s.\n462\t− − →\n463\t¯ψ(y,S;x). Residual term:Since |RJ | ≤B ,\n464\t\n465\t\n466\tJ RJ\n467\t\n468\t\n469\t ≤\n470\tB\n471\tJ →0.\n472\tThus uJ(y)\n473\ta.s.\n474\t− − →¯ψ(y,S;x) for each y. Since Y is fi-\n475\tnite, this convergence is uniform over y. Now, the nor-\n476\tmalized distribution pJ can be written as, with ymax =\n477\targ maxy′ uJ(y′):\n478\tpJ(y|x,C 1:J) = exp(J·u J(y))P\n479\ty′ exp(J·u J(y′))\n480\t= exp(uJ(y)−u J(ymax))P\n481\ty′ exp(uJ(y′)−u J(ymax)) .(8)\n482\tDefine vJ(y) :=u J(y)−max y′ uJ(y′) and, similarly,\n483\tv⋆(y) := ¯ψ(y,S;x)−max y′ ¯ψ(y ′,S;x) . Since uJ → ¯ψ\n484\tuniformly and taking the maximum is continuous on finite\n485\tsets, we havev J →v ⋆ uniformly.\n486\tThe softmax map v7→exp(v)/ P\n487\ty′ exp(v(y ′)) is continu-\n488\tous. Therefore:\n489\tpJ(y) = softmax(vJ)y\n490\ta.s.\n491\t− − →softmax(v⋆)y =p ⋆(y|x,S).\n492\tContinuity of theℓ 1 norm completes the proof.\n493\tRemark3.5 (Rate of convergence).The proof reveals that\n494\tconvergence occurs at the rate O(1/\n495\t√\n496\tJ) from the SLLN\n497\tplus O(1/J) from the vanishing residual and prior terms.\n498\tIn practice, this suggests that moderate values of J (e.g.,\n499\tJ= 20–50) should suffice for near-convergence.\n500\tRemark3.6 (Connection to our algorithm).Multiple\n501\tprivacy-preserving Algorithms, including ours, query each\n502\texample independently, i.e., computing p(y|C j,x) sepa-\n503\trately. Under Assumption 3.2, this independent querying\n504\tdiscards only the bounded residual RJ, which vanishes per\n505\tTheorem 3.4 as J grows. The theorem shows that, condi-\n506\ttional on the boundedness assumption, the error introduced\n507\tby independent querying vanishes asJ grows. This provides\n508\ta theoretical framework for understanding when indepen-\n509\tdent querying might be appropriate, and we present experi-\n510\tmental results in Section 4 that support the assumption, even\n511\twithout the noise required for DP.\n512\t3.3. Methodological comparison to prior approaches\n513\tIn the experimental results, we compare with three prior\n514\tapproaches. The first approach is named after the Report-\n515\tNoisy-Max (RNM) method (Dwork & Roth, 2014). The\n516\tmethod relies on the same conditional independence as-\n517\tsumption (Wu et al., 2024), but uses thresholded “hard\n518\tpredictions,” which discard the nuance of the predictive\n519\tlikelihoods. This would be achieved by replacing line 7\n520\tin Algorithm 1 with ˆy← ˆy+one-hot(arg maxl) , which\n521\tmeans that ˆy is updated with a vector of all zeros and a\n522\tsingle one where the largest likelihood occurs. The RNM\n523\tthen relies on observing that such a vector has sensitivity 1,\n524\tand adds proportionally scaled noise; we refer to their paper\n525\tfor the proof of the constants.\n526\tAnother approach towards the same DP guarantee is\n527\t‘Privacy-Amplification-by-Subsampling’ (PbS), which also\n528\tpreserves the ‘uncertainty nuance’ of predictions. Similar\n529\tto DP-SGD (Abadi et al., 2016), this method repeatedly\n530\tsamples subsets of the context to make noisy predictions,\n531\twhich are then averaged. This was suggested by Wu et al.\n532\t(2024), and we compare to it in the experimental section. A\n533\tmajor downside of this method is that it requires significant\n534\tcomputational resources. Due to the Poisson sampling as-\n535\tsumption (Chua et al., 2024b), potentially the entire context\n536\t\n537\t--- PAGE BREAK ---\n538\t\n539\tPrivate PoEtry: Private In-Context Learning via Product of Experts\n540\tTable 1.Comparison against prior art. For each dataset, the accuracy of each method is significantly higher than the 0-shot result,\n541\tdemonstrating ICL. For both 8 and 25 in-context examples across three datasets, our method achieves significantly higher accuracy. The\n542\tDP is set to ε= 4 , following prior work (Tang et al., 2024). The LLM is Qwen3-4B and Table 5 reproduces this table with Llama3.1-8B.\n543\tεNum data Method Lbl. Priv. AGNews DBPedia TREC\n544\tNo context 0 0 Empty✓65.4 ±0.8 71.2±1.0 68.4±0.7\n545\tSynthetic (Tang et al., 2024) 410 5 Synth. data ×79.8 ±0.7 81.9±0.6 76.3±1.1\n546\t8 context examples:\n547\tPrivacy-by-Sampling (Wu et al., 2024) 4 8 Subsampling✓80.7 ±0.5 70.3±0.9 72.2±0.9\n548\tRNM (Wu et al., 2024) 4 8 Hard voting✓65.5 ±0.6 46.3±0.8 52.4±0.9\n549\tProduct-of-Experts (ours) 4 8 Soft pred. ✓ 86.3±0.5 87.3±0.6 78.9±0.5\n550\t25 context examples:\n551\tPrivacy-by-Sampling (Wu et al., 2024) 4 25 Subsampling✓81.5 ±0.4 75.2±1.1 68.1±0.7\n552\tRNM (Wu et al., 2024) 4 25 Hard voting✓85.3 ±0.6 85.7±0.7 76.7±0.6\n553\tProduct-of-Experts (ours) 4 25 Soft pred. ✓ 87.0±0.5 88.0±0.6 78.8±0.5\n554\tNon-private, no DP applied∞8 In-context -87.5 ±0.5 89.9±0.5 80.5±0.8\n555\tNon-private, no DP applied∞25 In-context -87.8 ±0.6 92.0±0.7 81.0±0.7\n556\tTable 2.Results on arithmetic tasks in the GSM8k dataset. All\n557\tevaluations have higher accuracy than the 0-shot accuracy at 14% –\n558\tshowing the ICL benefit. Across varying numbers of ICL examples,\n559\tour method achieves significantly higher accuracy than RNM.\n560\tNumber of examples\n561\t4 8 20\n562\tNon-private, no DP44.2 ±1.0 44.5±0.8 46.0±0.9\n563\tRNM (Wu et al., 2024)15.7 ±0.6 20.3±0.5 36.5±0.6\n564\tPoE (Ours) 37.3±1.3 40.9±1.1 43.1±1.1\n565\tcould require computation in each random sample, of which\n566\tthere could be up to hundreds (Wu et al., 2024).\n567\t4. Experimental results\n568\tThe experimental evaluation and comparison with related\n569\twork are conducted across five datasets in three categories:\n570\ttext classification, grade-school math, and vision-language.\n571\tThis section also includes results from a Membership Infer-\n572\tence Attack to explore the attack scenario empirically.\n573\t4.1. Comparison of Hard or Soft predictions\n574\tFirst, we compare the thresholded against the soft predic-\n575\ttions that motivate our work. Soft predictions preserve\n576\tnuance in every prediction. For example, in a two-class pre-\n577\tdiction problem, two predictions might be 0.6 and 0.7 for\n578\tone class, 0.4 and 0.3 for the other. PoE will work with log-\n579\tprobabilities [log 0.6 + log 0.7,log 0.4 + log 0.3], instead of\n580\tthresholded[2,0]used for RNM.\n581\tTo empirically justify this approximation, we use the pre-\n582\tdictive likelihoods from the independent LLMs’ predictions\n583\tand compare the vectors from Hard V oting and Soft Predic-\n584\ttions. Let’s say one prediction overK classes would be p=\n585\t[p1, p2,· · ·, p K]∈[0,1] K. For hard voting, this would be\n586\tthresholded to h∈ {0,1}; P h= 1 . For soft predictions,\n587\tthis would be clipped tos= [s 1, s2,· · ·, s K]∈[e −γ,1] K.\n588\tWe compare the predictive likelihood at the target label\n589\tlmean(q, y) =q y for approximate vector q at label y. q\n590\tcould be either the hard thresholded h or the clipped s. The\n591\tpredictive likelihood is important because it is the prob-\n592\tability that this expert alone will sample the target label\n593\tclass. Secondly, we compare the ℓ∞-norm D∞(p,q) =\n594\tmaxi |pi −q i| norm, which indicates the largest change\n595\tin sampling probability between the unclipped vector, p,\n596\tand thresholded or clipped q. To this end, we sample 3000\n597\tcontext and query examples from the GSM8k classifica-\n598\ttion task (Cobbe et al., 2021) and make predictions with\n599\ta Qwen3 model (Team Qwen, 2025). Compared between\n600\thard and soft predictions, the predictive likelihood increases\n601\tfrom 42.3±0.6% to 45.3±0.9% and the ℓ∞-norm decreases\n602\tfrom 39.2±0.5% to 13.5±0.1%. This shows that the mean\n603\tpredictive likelihood and the ℓ∞-norm are much better for\n604\tsoft predictions. These results motivate our method, since\n605\tDP methods must sample from those private states.\n606\t4.2. Text classification\n607\tText classificationThe evaluation tasks involve 4-way news\n608\tclassification on AGNEWS(Zhang et al., 2015), 6-way ques-\n609\ttion categorization on the TREC dataset (V oorhees & Tice,\n610\t2000), and 14-way entity classification on the DBPEDIA\n611\t\n612\t--- PAGE BREAK ---\n613\t\n614\tPrivate PoEtry: Private In-Context Learning via Product of Experts\n615\t1 2 4 8 16 25 32\n616\tNumber of in-context examples\n617\t80Accuracy\n618\t+30% \n619\tperformance\n620\t-75% samples\n621\tNo DP RNM PoE\n622\tFigure 2.Average accuracy across AGNews, DBPedia, TREC, and\n623\tGSM8k datasets. Our method performs significantly better than\n624\tprevious work – especially for a small number of examples, where\n625\tICL is widely used. For J= 4 examples, the improvement in\n626\taccuracy is 30% points on average. To achieve the same accuracy,\n627\tRNM would need almost 4x as many in-context examples.\n628\tdataset (Zhang et al., 2015). This evaluation follows the\n629\tsetup of Zhao et al. (2021); Tang et al. (2024), and we use\n630\tthe prompt settings from the published code of Tang et al.\n631\t(2024). Their models are not available, so we evaluate their\n632\tcode with a Qwen3-4B model. Appendix D reproduces this\n633\texperiment with a Llama3.1-8B model. The success metric\n634\tis classification accuracy. Each accuracy is a mean (and\n635\t± standard error) of 25 random seeds; each random seed\n636\tis the evaluation of 100 random prompts from the test set\n637\tagainst a randomly drawn context set. To be comparable\n638\twith previous work, evaluations for this task are done at\n639\tε= 4 . Where Approximate DP applies, δ= 10 −5 is used.\n640\tMore details are provided in Appendix E.\n641\tTable 1 shows the results of the text classification experi-\n642\tments. It is important to note that the synthetic data method\n643\tof Tang et al. (2024) provides a privacy guarantee against\n644\ta training dataset of about 100,000+ examples. In contrast,\n645\tfor both PbS, RNM, and our method, the privacy guaran-\n646\ttee holds against the actual context set, as explained in\n647\tAppendix B.3. Despite this difference, the synthetic data\n648\tmethod achieves lower accuracy than our method.\n649\tAcross all three text classification datasets, our method\n650\tachieves higher accuracy than other methods. Especially for\n651\ta small number of examples, which is an important setting\n652\tfor in-context learning (Cobbe et al., 2021; Tsimpoukelli\n653\tet al., 2021), our method scores more than 20% points higher\n654\taccuracy than RNM and more than 6% points higher than\n655\tPbS. This is likely due to the uncertainty information pre-\n656\tserved in the soft predictions, c.f. Section 4.1.\n657\tMath evaluation:The math evaluation is done on the\n658\tGSM8Kdataset (Cobbe et al., 2021). This dataset consists\n659\tof math or arithmetic questions aimed at the level of grade-\n660\tschoolers. We turn this into a 10-way classification task by\n661\tTable 3.Results on the VLM pseudoname labelling task. Across\n662\tvarying numbers of in-context examples, our method achieves\n663\thigher accuracy. For comparison, also the non-private but condi-\n664\ttionally independent results are included; 0-shot accuracy is 20%.\n665\tNumber of examples\n666\t4 8 20\n667\tNon-private, no DP89.0 ±0.6 89.1±0.6 89.8±0.6\n668\tSoft cond. indep.82.6 ±0.8 82.7±0.8 83.3±0.8\n669\tHard cond. indep.76.0 ±0.9 80.7±0.8 82.6±0.8\n670\tRNM (Wu et al., 2024)28.8 ±0.9 39.4±1.0 69.8±0.9\n671\tPoE (Ours) 35.1±1.0 53.7±1.0 78.7±0.8\n672\tcalculating accuracy on getting the first digit of the answer\n673\tcorrect. Although this evaluation is not standard, the accu-\n674\tracy is significantly higher than the default 10% accuracy,\n675\tdemonstrating the LLMs’ mathematical capabilities.\n676\tTable 2 displays the results of the math evaluation on\n677\tGSM8k. Across a number of examples, our method achieves\n678\thigher accuracy than RNM. This aligns with the text classi-\n679\tfication results. Also, for a smaller number of examples, the\n680\timprovement over RNM is more pronounced, which is an\n681\timportant aspect of in-context learning.\n682\tResults across a varying number of examplesTo assess\n683\tperformance across the full range of in-context learning use\n684\tcases, we evaluate all four text classification datasets across\n685\ta varying number of examples (Figure 2). The practically\n686\trelevant regime for ICL is 4–8 examples (Min et al., 2022),\n687\twhere few-shot learning significantly improves over zero-\n688\tshot performance. Here, our method outperforms RNM by\n689\t30% points at 4 examples, and to achieve comparable accu-\n690\tracy, RNM requires 4x as many context examples (16). This\n691\tshows that our method is effective at improving accuracy in\n692\tthe practically relevant regime for in-context learning.\n693\t4.3. Vision-language\n694\tTo demonstrate that our method is not only effective with\n695\ttext tokens but also applicable across modalities, we conduct\n696\ta final experiment using a vision-language model. For sim-\n697\tplicity, we focus on the task of pseudo-name labelling (Tsim-\n698\tpoukelli et al., 2021). In this task, a Vision-Language Model\n699\t(VLM) is shown images and randomly assigned non-English\n700\tnames to them. The VLM will then be prompted with\n701\tan image, and it must classify the image’s name. It is a\n702\t5-way classification task. We choose this pseudo-name\n703\tlabelling setting so that the VLM cannot rely on pretrain-\n704\ting knowledge and must learn from in-context examples.\n705\tPrevious work has established that this task is suitable for\n706\tin-context learning (Tsimpoukelli et al., 2021; Derakhshani\n707\tet al., 2023). Similar to earlier experiments, the error bars\n708\t\n709\t--- PAGE BREAK ---\n710\t\n711\tPrivate PoEtry: Private In-Context Learning via Product of Experts\n712\tTable 4.Empirical privacy vulnerability as measured by a Mem-\n713\tbership Inference Attack. These results show a significant attack\n714\tvulnerability (AUROC 56-93%), and DP significantly reduces the\n715\tvulnerability, i.e., an AUROC close to the target value of 50%.\n716\tAGNews DBpedia TREC GSM8k\n717\tNo DP 60.0 56.9 63.6 93.9\n718\tε= 1DP 52.9 49.8 53.8 53.5\n719\tin Table 3 are the standard error of the mean accuracy over\n720\t2500 random seeds, explained in Appendix E.\n721\tTable 3 displays the results of the vision-language evalua-\n722\ttion. These results were obtained with ε= 1 -DP, which is\n723\tthe recommended setting by Hsu et al. (2014) and Wood\n724\tet al. (2018). Across a number of examples, our method\n725\tachieves higher accuracy than RNM. This aligns with the\n726\ttext classification and math evaluation results. Also, for a\n727\tsmaller number of examples, which are widely used in ICL,\n728\tthe improvement over RNM is more pronounced.\n729\tComparison of the conditional independence assumption:\n730\tWe also investigate the difference between Hard and Soft\n731\tpredictions in a classification setting. To this end, Table 3\n732\tshows the accuracies when only the conditional indepen-\n733\tdence assumption is applied, but the noise required for DP\n734\tis not yet added. This means that for Hard predictions, only\n735\tthe discrete votes are summed, and the class with the most\n736\tvotes is predicted. For soft predictions, this means that the\n737\tclipped predictions are multiplied, and the class with the\n738\thighest likelihood is predicted. For both the Hard and the\n739\tSoft versions, the accuracy is lower than the non-private\n740\tresult, which is expected, as we introduce a strict assump-\n741\ttion. However, the decrease in accuracy is much larger for\n742\tHard predictions than for soft predictions. Moreover, this\n743\tdecrease is much worse for a small number of examples\n744\t– likely because the uncertainty in predictive likelihood is\n745\tmore important. This shows that, even in the absence of DP\n746\tnoise addition or noisy sampling, Hard predictions have a\n747\tworse impact on the final accuracy than soft predictions.\n748\t4.4. Membership Inference Attack\n749\tComplementary to the analytical privacy guarantees, we\n750\trun a Membership Inference Attack (MIA) (Shokri et al.,\n751\t2017) to obtain empirical results on privacy. Although a\n752\tMIA cannot prove that the model uses a particular data\n753\tpoint (Zhang et al., 2025), we investigate if the original\n754\tICL is vulnerable to an empirical privacy attack and to what\n755\textent our DP guarantee reduces this vulnerability. The MIA\n756\taims to output a score, s, indicating whether a datapoint\n757\tis a member of the context examples. Several MIAs have\n758\tbeen reported in the literature (Chang et al., 2025; Carlini\n759\tet al., 2021), and we use the attack based on Likelihood\n760\tRatios (LiRA). We use likelihood-based MIA as a proxy\n761\tfor privacy vulnerability on sampled labels. In our case,\n762\tthe summed log-likelihood is the score s. While label-only\n763\tMIAs exist (He et al., 2025), they have only been shown to\n764\twork for longer sequences by approximating soft likelihood.\n765\tFor simplicity, we use the proxy directly. A comparatively\n766\thigh score indicates membership, and this is measured using\n767\tthe Area Under the ROC curve (AUROC) metric. The\n768\tAUROC is the area under the curve on a plot where the\n769\tx-axis is the False Positive Rate (flagging a member when it\n770\tis not) and the True Positive Rate (flagging a member when\n771\tit is). Appendix E.2 provides more details.\n772\tThe results of the MIA are in Table 4. The unprotected ICL\n773\tsetting is vulnerable to a membership inference attack, as\n774\tindicated by an AUROC of 60.0 on the AGNews dataset,\n775\tfor example. Subsequently, the DP ICL has an AUROC\n776\tof 52.9 on AGNews, indicating better privacy protection.\n777\tThe same trend, where the DP model is much closer to\n778\t50.0, is observed for the other datasets. This shows that, in\n779\taddition to the theoretical privacy guarantees, DP ICL is\n780\talso empirically more private against MIAs.\n781\t5. Conclusion\n782\tWe introduce a novel approach to differentially private in-\n783\tcontext learning that reformulates ICL through the lens of a\n784\tProduct-of-Experts (PoE) approximation. Our key contribu-\n785\ttion is the shift fromhard votingtosoft predictionaggrega-\n786\ttion. This enables our method to leverage the full uncertainty\n787\tinformation in the model’s predictive probabilities. This un-\n788\tcertainty information is shown to be beneficial compared\n789\tto prior approaches that discard the uncertainty through dis-\n790\tcrete thresholding. The soft prediction approach, where\n791\tlog-probabilities across in-context examples are clipped and\n792\taggregated, proves particularly effective for a small number\n793\tof examples (four to eight examples), which is the common\n794\tsetting in many real-world ICL applications.\n795\tOur experimental evaluation demonstrates consistent im-\n796\tprovements across five datasets including text classification,\n797\tmath, and vision-language tasks. On average, we observe\n798\ta 30% point improvement for text classification with only\n799\t4 examples. Beyond empirical performance, we provide"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_012BWpww6hxu8oGW4VqL6HYH","session_id":"61b992b7-c7e9-4fd1-9cce-d1e8223d902f","uuid":"58176994-414a-4381-bb9e-db6296cab609","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:40:24.333Z"}
