{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Jf9L8h573rx5RvSBmae4uS","type":"tool_result","content":"800\tboth theoretical and empirical analyses of privacy. Theoreti-\n801\tcally, we propose an algorithm that guarantees Differential\n802\tprivacy. Additionally, we establish that under a bounded-\n803\tinteraction assumption, our Product-of-Experts approxima-\n804\ttion converges to the full-context distribution as the number\n805\tof examples increases. Empirically, we complement the\n806\tprivacy guarantee with a Membership Inference Attack on\n807\tfour datasets. Overall, the improved privacy-utility trade-off\n808\tmakes our method practical for deployment in agentic AI\n809\tand RAG settings where privacy-sensitive local data must\n810\tbe leveraged without compromising an individual’s privacy.\n811\t\n812\t--- PAGE BREAK ---\n813\t\n814\tPrivate PoEtry: Private In-Context Learning via Product of Experts\n815\tImpact Statement\n816\tOur work advances private machine learning by enabling\n817\tmore effective privacy-preserving in-context learning. DP\n818\tcould have a positive societal impact by allowing systems to\n819\tuse local private information while providing formal privacy\n820\tguarantees. The improved privacy-utility trade-off makes\n821\tDP ICL more accessible for real-world deployment.\n822\tHowever, while DP provides rigorous guarantees, organi-\n823\tzations must remain thoughtful about its deployment. We\n824\twarrant that DP cannot be used as a blanket justification for\n825\tadditional data access – although this effect remains an open\n826\tquestion (Brough et al., 2022). Each deployment of any ICL\n827\tvariant should justify processing the data in contexts where\n828\tdata minimization would also be an option.\n829\tSecond, we acknowledge that differentially private meth-\n830\tods can have disparate impacts across different groups in\n831\tthe data. Prior research has demonstrated that privacy-\n832\tpreserving mechanisms may disproportionately affect model\n833\tperformance on minority classes and underrepresented pop-\n834\tulations (Farrand et al., 2020; Bagdasaryan et al., 2019).\n835\tWhile our theoretical and empirical contributions improve\n836\toverall privacy-utility trade-offs, they do not directly address\n837\tthese fairness concerns. Future work should investigate how\n838\tthe Product-of-Experts approximation interacts with fair-\n839\tness objectives and develop techniques to ensure equitable\n840\tutility across demographic groups.\n841\tReferences\n842\tAbadi, M., Chu, A., Goodfellow, I., McMahan, H. B.,\n843\tMironov, I., Talwar, K., and Zhang, L. Deep learning with\n844\tdifferential privacy. InProceedings of the ACM SIGSAC\n845\tconference on computer and communications security,\n846\t2016.\n847\tAgarwal, R., Singh, A., Zhang, L., Bohnet, B., Rosias, L.,\n848\tChan, S., Zhang, B., Anand, A., Abbas, Z., Nova, A.,\n849\tet al. Many-shot in-context learning.Advances in Neural\n850\tInformation Processing Systems (NeurIPS), 2024.\n851\tBagdasaryan, E., Poursaeed, O., and Shmatikov, V . Dif-\n852\tferential privacy has disparate impact on model accu-\n853\tracy.Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems\n854\t(NeurIPS), 2019.\n855\tBalle, B., Barthe, G., and Gaboardi, M. Privacy amplifica-\n856\ttion by subsampling: Tight analyses via couplings and\n857\tdivergences.Advances in Neural Information Processing\n858\tSystems (NeurIPS), 2018.\n859\tBrough, A. R., Norton, D. A., Sciarappa, S. L., and John,\n860\tL. K. The bulletproof glass effect: Unintended conse-\n861\tquences of privacy notices.Journal of Marketing Re-\n862\tsearch, 2022.\n863\tBrown, T. B., Mann, B., Ryder, N., Subbiah, M., Kaplan,\n864\tJ., Dhariwal, P., Neelakantan, A., Shyam, P., Sastry, G.,\n865\tAskell, A., Agarwal, S., Herbert-V oss, A., Krueger, G.,\n866\tHenighan, T., Child, R., Ramesh, A., Ziegler, D. M., Wu,\n867\tJ., Winter, C., Hesse, C., Chen, M., Sigler, E., Litwin, M.,\n868\tGray, S., Chess, B., Clark, J., Berner, C., McCandlish,\n869\tS., Radford, A., Sutskever, I., and Amodei, D. Language\n870\tmodels are few-shot learners. InAdvances in Neural\n871\tInformation Processing Systems (NeurIPS), 2020.\n872\tCarey, A. N., Bhaila, K., Edemacu, K., and Wu, X. Dp-\n873\ttabicl: In-context learning with differentially private tab-\n874\tular data. InIEEE International Conference on Big Data\n875\t(BigData), 2024.\n876\tCarlini, N., Tram`er, F., Wallace, E., Jagielski, M., Herbert-\n877\tV oss, A., Lee, K., Roberts, A., Brown, T. B., Song, D.,\n878\tErlingsson, ´U., Oprea, A., and Raffel, C. Extracting\n879\ttraining data from large language models. InUSENIX\n880\tSecurity Symposium, 2021.\n881\tChang, H., Shamsabadi, A. S., Katevas, K., Haddadi, H.,\n882\tand Shokri, R. Context-aware membership inference at-\n883\ttacks against pre-trained large language models.Proceed-\n884\tings of the Conference on Empirical Methods in Natural\n885\tLanguage Processing, (EMNLP), 2025.\n886\tChoi, J., Cao, S., Dong, X., and Karimireddy, S. P. Con-\n887\ttextleak: Auditing leakage in private in-context learning\n888\tmethods. InThe Impact of Memorization on Trustworthy\n889\tFoundation Models: ICML 2025 Workshop.\n890\tChua, L., Ghazi, B., Huang, Y ., Kamath, P., Kumar, R., Liu,\n891\tD., Manurangsi, P., Sinha, A., and Zhang, C. Mind the\n892\tprivacy unit! user-level differential privacy for language\n893\tmodel fine-tuning.Conference on Language Modeling\n894\t(COLM), 2024a.\n895\tChua, L., Ghazi, B., Kamath, P., Kumar, R., Manurangsi,\n896\tP., Sinha, A., and Zhang, C. How private are dp-sgd\n897\timplementations?International Conference on Machine\n898\tLearning (ICML), 2024b.\n899\tCobbe, K., Kosaraju, V ., Bavarian, M., Chen, M., Jun, H.,\n900\tKaiser, L., Plappert, M., Tworek, J., Hilton, J., Nakano,\n901\tR., et al. Training verifiers to solve math word problems.\n902\tarXiv 2110.14168, 2021.\n903\tDeng, J., Dong, W., Socher, R., Li, L.-J., Li, K., and Fei-Fei,\n904\tL. Imagenet: A large-scale hierarchical image database.\n905\tInProceedings of the Conference on Computer Vision\n906\tand Pattern Recognition (CVPR), 2009.\n907\tDerakhshani, M. M., Najdenkoska, I., Snoek, C. G., Wor-\n908\tring, M., and Asano, Y . M. Self-supervised open-ended\n909\tclassification with small visual language models.ICLR\n910\tME-FoMo Workshop (arXiv 2310.00500), 2023.\n911\t\n912\t--- PAGE BREAK ---\n913\t\n914\tPrivate PoEtry: Private In-Context Learning via Product of Experts\n915\tDuan, H., Dziedzic, A., Papernot, N., and Boenisch, F.\n916\tFlocks of stochastic parrots: Differentially private prompt\n917\tlearning for large language models.Advances in Neural\n918\tInformation Processing Systems (NeurIPS), 2023a.\n919\tDuan, H., Dziedzic, A., Yaghini, M., Papernot, N., and\n920\tBoenisch, F. On the privacy risk of in-context learning.\n921\tProceedings of the Annual Meeting of the Association for\n922\tComputational Linguistics (ACL), 2023b.\n923\tDubey, A., Jauhri, A., Pandey, A., Kadian, A., Al-Dahle,\n924\tA., Letman, A., Mathur, A., Schelten, A., Yang, A., Fan,\n925\tA., et al. The llama 3 herd of models.arXiv 2407.21783,\n926\t2024.\n927\tDwork, C. and Roth, A. The algorithmic foundations of\n928\tdifferential privacy.Theoretical Computer Science, 2014.\n929\tFan, S., Ding, X., Zhang, L., and Mo, L. Mcptoolbench++:\n930\tA large scale ai agent model context protocol mcp tool\n931\tuse benchmark.arXiv 2508.07575, 2025.\n932\tFarrand, T., Mireshghallah, F., Singh, S., and Trask, A.\n933\tNeither private nor fair: Impact of data imbalance on\n934\tutility and fairness in differential privacy. InProceedings\n935\tof the 2020 workshop on privacy-preserving machine\n936\tlearning in practice, 2020.\n937\tFlemings, J., Razaviyayn, M., and Annavaram, M. Differ-\n938\tentially private next-token prediction of large language\n939\tmodels.Proceedings of the Annual Meeting of the Asso-\n940\tciation for Computational Linguistics (