i-experts.\n975\tInProceedings of the Annual Meeting of the Association\n976\tfor Computational Linguistics (ACL), 2021.\n977\tMandelbrot, B. Structure formelle des textes et communica-\n978\ttion: Deux ´etudes par. 1954.\n979\tMin, S., Lyu, X., Holtzman, A., Artetxe, M., Lewis, M.,\n980\tHajishirzi, H., and Zettlemoyer, L. Rethinking the role of\n981\tdemonstrations: What makes in-context learning work?\n982\tProceedings of the Conference on Empirical Methods in\n983\tNatural Language Processing, (EMNLP), 2022.\n984\tPapernot, N., Abadi, M., Erlingsson, U., Goodfellow, I.,\n985\tand Talwar, K. Semi-supervised knowledge transfer for\n986\tdeep learning from private training data.International\n987\tConference on Learning Representations (ICLR), 2017.\n988\tRaisa, O., Jalko, J., and Honkela, A. Subsampling is not\n989\tmagic: Why large batch sizes work for differentially\n990\tprivate stochastic optimisation.International Conference\n991\ton Machine Learning (ICML), 2024.\n992\tRomijnders, R. and Koskela, A. Convex approximation\n993\tof two-layer relu networks for hidden state differential\n994\tprivacy.Advances in Neural Information Processing\n995\tSystems (NeurIPS), 2025.\n996\tRomijnders, R., Laskaridis, S., Shamsabadi, A. S., and\n997\tHaddadi, H. Noesis: Differentially private knowledge\n998\ttransfer in modular llm adaptation.Proceedings of the In-\n999\tternational Association for Safe and Ethical AI (IASEAI),\n1000\t2026.\n1001\tShokri, R., Stronati, M., Song, C., and Shmatikov, V . Mem-\n1002\tbership inference attacks against machine learning mod-\n1003\tels. InSymposium on security and privacy (SP). IEEE,\n1004\t2017.\n1005\tSinha, A., Mesnard, T., McKenna, R., Liu, D., Choquette-\n1006\tChoo, C. A., Huang, Y ., Yu, D., Kaissis, G., Charles,\n1007\tZ., Liu, R., et al. Vaultgemma: A differentially private\n1008\tgemma model.arXiv 2510.15001, 2025.\n1009\t\n1010\t--- PAGE BREAK ---\n1011\t\n1012\tPrivate PoEtry: Private In-Context Learning via Product of Experts\n1013\tSun, Z., Tian, Z., Song, Y ., Si, Y ., Zhang, J., Huang, M.,\n1014\tLu, K., Xiong, Z., Liu, X., and Li, D. Dpga-textsyn:\n1015\tDifferentially private genetic algorithm for synthetic text\n1016\tgeneration. InProceedings of the Annual Meeting of the\n1017\tAssociation for Computational Linguistics (ACL), 2025.\n1018\tTang, X., Shin, R., Inan, H. A., Manoel, A., Mireshghallah,\n1019\tF., Lin, Z., Gopi, S., Kulkarni, J., and Sim, R. Privacy-\n1020\tpreserving in-context learning with differentially private\n1021\tfew-shot generation.International Conference on Learn-\n1022\ting Representations (ICLR), 2024.\n1023\tTeam Qwen. Qwen3 technical report.arXiv 2505.09388,\n1024\t2025.\n1025\tTsimpoukelli, M., Menick, J., Cabi, S., Eslami, S., Vinyals,\n1026\tO., and Hill, F. Multimodal few-shot learning with frozen\n1027\tlanguage models.Advances in Neural Information Pro-\n1028\tcessing Systems (NeurIPS), 2021.\n1029\tV oorhees, E. M. and Tice, D. M. Building a question an-\n1030\tswering test collection. InProceedings of the annual\n1031\tinternational ACM SIGIR conference on Research and\n1032\tdevelopment in information retrieval, 2000.\n1033\tWang, B., Chen, W., Pei, H., Xie, C., Kang, M., Zhang,\n1034\tC., Xu, C., Xiong, Z., Dutta, R., Schaeffer, R., et al.\n1035\tDecodingtrust: A comprehensive assessment of trustwor-\n1036\tthiness in gpt models. InAdvances in Neural Information\n1037\tProcessing Systems (NeurIPS), 2023.\n1038\tWang, P., Bai, S., Tan, S., Wang, S., Fan, Z., Bai, J., Chen,\n1039\tK., Liu, X., Wang, J., Ge, W., Fan, Y ., Dang, K., Du, M.,\n1040\tRen, X., Men, R., Liu, D., Zhou, C., Zhou, J., and Lin, J.\n1041\tQwen2-vl: Enhancing vision-language model’s percep-\n1042\ttion of the world at any resolution.arXiv 2409.12191,\n1043\t2024.\n1044\tWood, A., Altman, M., Bembenek, A., Bun, M., Gaboardi,\n1045\tM., Honaker, J., Nissim, K., O’Brien, D. R., Steinke, T.,\n1046\tand Vadhan, S. Differential privacy: A primer for a non-\n1047\ttechnical audience.Vanderbilt Journal of Entertainment\n1048\tand Technology Law, 2018.\n1049\tWu, T., Panda, A., Wang, J. T., and Mittal, P. Privacy-\n1050\tpreserving in-context learning for large language models.\n1051\tInternational Conference on Learning Representations\n1052\t(ICLR), 2024.\n1053\tYousefpour, A., Shilov, I., Sablayrolles, A., Testuggine, D.,\n1054\tPrasad, K., Malek, M., Nguyen, J., Ghosh, S., Bharadwaj,\n1055\tA., Zhao, J., Cormode, G., and Mironov, I. Opacus: User-\n1056\tfriendly differential privacy library in PyTorch.arXiv\n1057\t2109.12298, 2021.\n1058\tYu, D., Naik, S., Backurs, A., Gopi, S., Inan, H. A., Ka-\n1059\tmath, G., Kulkarni, J., Lee, Y . T., Manoel, A., Wutschitz,\n1060\tL., et al. Differentially private fine-tuning of language\n1061\tmodels. InInternational Conference on Learning Repre-\n1062\tsentations (ICLR), 2021.\n1063\tZhang, J., Das, D., Kamath, G., and Tram`er, F. Membership\n1064\tinference attacks cannot prove that a model was trained on\n1065\tyour data.IEEE Conference on Secure and Trustworthy\n1066\tMachine Learning (SaTML), 2025.\n1067\tZhang, X., Zhao, J., and LeCun, Y . Character-level con-\n1068\tvolutional networks for text classification.Advances in\n1069\tNeural Information Processing Systems (NeurIPS), 2015.\n1070\tZhao, S., Brekelmans, R., Makhzani, A., and Grosse, R. B.\n1071\tProbabilistic inference in language models via twisted\n1072\tsequential monte carlo. InInternational Conference on\n1073\tMachine Learning (ICML), 2024.\n1074\tZhao, Z., Wallace, E., Feng, S., Klein, D., and Singh, S.\n1075\tCalibrate before use: Improving few-shot performance\n1076\tof language models. InInternational Conference on\n1077\tMachine Learning (ICML), 2021.\n1078\tZhu, J., Wang, W., Chen, Z., Liu, Z., Ye, S., Gu, L., Tian,\n1079\tH., Duan, Y ., Su, W., Shao, J., et al. Internvl3: Exploring\n1080\tadvanced training and test-time recipes for open-source\n1081\tmultimodal models.arXiv 2504.10479, 2025.\n1082\t\n1083\t--- PAGE BREAK ---\n1084\t\n1085\tPrivate PoEtry: Private In-Context Learning via Product of Experts\n1086\tA. Notation\n1087\tWe briefly outline the notation used in the main paper and in the following appendices.\n1088\t•γis the clipping bound for the log-probabilities;\n1089\t•σ is the noise multiplier for the exponential mechanism. This is tightly related to theε parameter for Differential Privacy.\n1090\tFor example, in Algorithm 1,σ= 1\n1091\tT εwhen the Product-of-Experts is used withTsteps and naive composition;\n1092\t•Tis the maximum number of tokens in the response;\n1093\t•Jis the number of in-context examples;\n1094\t•C j is thej-th in-context example;\n1095\t•xis the query, it is a sequence of tokens;\n1096\t•y <t is the response up to and including timet−1;\n1097\t•y t is the token at time t, sometimes the subscript is dropped to have just y; y1:T indicates the response sequence for all\n1098\tTtokens;\n1099\t•l is a vector of log-likelihoods, for example, when in Algorithm 1: “l←LM(·|z,x,C j),” then l is a vector of length\n1100\tequal to the vocabulary of the LLM where each valuel i is the log-likelihood for tokeni;\n1101\t•u(y,C j) is the utility function for the exponential mechanism. It is the log-probability of the response y given asingle\n1102\tin-context exampleC j;\n1103\t•U(y,C 1:J) is the utility function whenallthe in-context examples C1:J are considered; this distinction will be made\n1104\tmore clear in Appendix B.2;\n1105\t• clip γ(l)is the clipping function for the log-probabilities. It sets all values outside the interval[−γ,0]to zero;\n1106\t• vclip γ(l)in the section on Gaussian Mechanism is the vector clipping function vclip γ(x) =x/max(γ,∥x∥ 2);\n1107\t•Zis, unless otherwise specified, a constant of proportionality – a normalization constant;\n1108\t•ε and δ are constants that define the Differential Privacy guarantee; generally,ε≤1 and δ≤10 −5 are preferred. Only\n1109\tfor Tables 1 and 5 do we useε= 4, to follow previous work and their implementation details (Tang et al., 2024);\n1110\t•Dis a dataset, so a collection of documents, denoted byC j forj= 1, . . . , J.\n1111\tApart from notation, we clarify that with ‘prompt’ we mean the entire textual input to an LLM, which consists of both a\n1112\tquery and context examples. Abstractly written, prompt=query+context examples.\n1113\tB. Details of the Differential Privacy Analysis\n1114\tB.1. Privacy for Algorithm 1\n1115\tThis section is an extended proof that Algorithm 1 satisfies Differential Privacy for defined settings ofσ and T . We start\n1116\tfrom the Product-of-Experts structure, repeated from Equation 2,p(y t|y<t,x,C 1:J)∝ Q\n1117\tj p(yt|y<t,x,C j).\n1118\tThis structure is chosen such that the contribution of each context example, Cj, is isolated. As such, we repeat the definition\n1119\tof Differential Privacy from Dwork & Roth (2014).\n1120\tA randomized algorithm A(·) is ε-differentially private if the following holds\n1121\tfor any two adjacent datasetsD,D ′, and for any subsetSof outputs:\n1122\tPr[A(D)∈ S]≤e ε Pr[A(D′)∈ S],(9)\n1123\twhere D={C j}J\n1124\tj=1 is a dataset that contains J documents and D′ is\n1125\tthe same dataset where at most one sample is different. This adjacency\n1126\tis further explained in Section B.3. In some cases, to Equation 9 a small\n1127\tconstant δ is added which is usually 10−6. The definition is then named\n1128\t“(ε, δ)(Approximate) Differential Privacy.”\n1129\t\n1130\t--- PAGE BREAK ---\n1131\t\n1132\tPrivate PoEtry: Private In-Context Learning via Product of Experts\n1133\tIn our case, this translates to“For any set of in-context examples, if only one example were different, the probability of the\n1134\tpredicted class would differ by at most a factore ε. ”\n1135\tOur randomized algorithm is the Exponential Mechanism from Dwork & Roth (2014), and works as follows. There is a\n1136\ttoken y, from a discrete set of tokens Y. Depending on the context, C1:J, there is a utility function u(y,C j). This utility\n1137\tfollows from Equation 3, which we repeat here.\n1138\tlog\n1139\tJY\n1140\tj=1\n1141\tp(yt|y<t,x,C j) =\n1142\tJX\n1143\tj=1\n1144\tlogp(y t|y<t,x,C j).(10)\n1145\tAs such, the utility reflects logp(y t|y<t,x,C j). The sensitivity, then, can be bounded by the clipping operation. We take\n1146\tthe likelihood factorl=u(y t,C j) = logp(y t|y<t,x,C j)and the clipping function clip γ(l):\n1147\tFor scalarl: clip γ(l) =\n1148\t(\n1149\tlif−γ≤l≤0\n1150\t0otherwise ,For vectorl: clip γ(l)i =\n1151\t(\n1152\tli if−γ≤l i ≤0\n1153\t0otherwise (11)\n1154\tThe upper clipping at 0 is trivially achieved, as the log-likelihood is always negative because, for a discrete domain, the\n1155\tprobability assigned to a class is less than or equal to 1. This maps to the definition of sensitivity in Dwork & Roth (2014)\n1156\tand we use their Exponential Mechanism with the following distribution:\n1157\tPr[y]∝e\n1158\tε\n1159\t2γ\n1160\tPJ\n1161\tj=1 u(y,Cj ) (12)\n1162\tIn this notation,σ=εwhen the Product-of-Experts is used withT= 1.\n1163\tAccountingThe σ in Algorithm 1 could be used for privacy accounting over the multiple tokens T . By composition\n1164\trules of DP ε=T σ , which evenly divides the ε among the T time steps (Dwork & Roth, 2014). One can use the\n1165\tAdvanced Composition Theorem of Differential privacy (Kairouz et al., 2015) if one is willing to switch to “Approximate\n1166\tDifferential Privacy:” ε=T σ(e σ −1) +σ\n1167\tp\n1168\t2Tlogδ −1 for a desired setting of δ. This composition theorem can be\n1169\tadvantageous because of the\n1170\t√\n1171\tT scaling rather than linear scaling. In case of the Report-Noisy-Max, we refer to the original\n1172\tpublication (Wu et al., 2024) for the relation between σ, T , and ε and δ. The experiments in Section 4 do not use accounting\n1173\tsince the classification predictions have single-token outputs.\n1174\tB.2. Grouping in L2 sensitivity\n1175\tIn related work (Tang et al., 2024), as well as ours, a method is used that we call “grouping.” We define and explain it in this\n1176\tsection for both our method and highlight how it was used in previous work.\n1177\tWhen clipping utilities for the Exponential Mechanism, or when clipping vectors as in the Gaussian Mechanism, it is\n1178\tcommon practice to align the clipping unit with the privacy unit (Abadi et al., 2016; Chua et al., 2024a). For document-level\n1179\tprivacy, for example, this would mean that the contribution of each document would be clipped separately. However, one\n1180\tcan “group” privacy units into clipping units and maintain the proof of Differential Privacy. We outline this method for the\n1181\texponential mechanism and the Gaussian Mechanism.\n1182\tExponential Mechanism\n1183\tThe exponential mechanism is defined as: Pr[y]∝e\n1184\tε\n1185\t2∆ U(y,D) , where y is the token, and U(y,D) is the utility function for\n1186\tthe full datasetD. The sensitivity is:\n1187\t∆ = max\n1188\tD∼D ′\n1189\t|U(y,D)−U(y,D ′)| ∀y∈ Y(13)\n1190\tThen, sampling a token y is ε-differentially private. Now, assume there is an arbitrary loss function u(y,D i), then one can\n1191\tensure bounded utility by clipping the loss function, where the clipping function is defined in Equation 11:\n1192\tu(y,D) :=\n1193\tX\n1194\ti∈|D|\n1195\tclipγ(u′(y,D i))(14)\n1196\t\n1197\t--- PAGE BREAK ---\n1198\t\n1199\tPrivate PoEtry: Private In-Context Learning via Product of Experts"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_012BWpww6hxu8oGW4VqL6HYH","session_id":"61b992b7-c7e9-4fd1-9cce-d1e8223d902f","uuid":"af8c0958-a57c-4d74-ae6c-33fafd5ae697","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:40:27.200Z"}
